WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.440 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.440 --> 00:00:03.904 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.904 --> 00:00:11.720 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:11.720 --> 00:00:13.680 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK.

00:00:13.680 --> 00:00:17.860 align:middle line:84%
So today we're going to
talk about the large sieve.

00:00:17.860 --> 00:00:20.640 align:middle line:84%
So last week, we
introduced the large sieve.

00:00:20.640 --> 00:00:24.520 align:middle line:84%
And we explained how it's
analogous to the projections

00:00:24.520 --> 00:00:26.260 align:middle line:84%
theorems that we proved
in finite fields,

00:00:26.260 --> 00:00:29.298 align:middle line:84%
and the projection theorems that
we proved in Euclidean space.

00:00:29.298 --> 00:00:30.840 align:middle line:84%
And today, I wanted
to explain to you

00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:34.920 align:middle line:84%
some of the applications of the
large sieve in number theory.

00:00:34.920 --> 00:00:38.980 align:middle line:84%
So the original application of
the large sieve was by Linnik.

00:00:38.980 --> 00:00:41.440 align:middle line:84%
And he was interested in
how quadratic residues are

00:00:41.440 --> 00:00:43.000 align:middle line:90%
distributed.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:45.580 align:middle line:84%
And I wrote that one
up on the homework.

00:00:45.580 --> 00:00:48.360 align:middle line:84%
So the homework problem is
to retrace Linnik's steps

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:52.960 align:middle line:84%
proving about how quadratic
residues are distributed.

00:00:52.960 --> 00:00:58.120 align:middle line:84%
And then a second important
influential application

00:00:58.120 --> 00:01:02.430 align:middle line:84%
has to do with how prime numbers
are distributed modulo q.

00:01:02.430 --> 00:01:06.950 align:middle line:84%
So that's what I'm going to
tell you all about today.

00:01:06.950 --> 00:01:11.830 align:middle line:84%
So first, we'll do
some background.

00:01:11.830 --> 00:01:13.870 align:middle line:84%
First, we'll talk
about what is known

00:01:13.870 --> 00:01:16.570 align:middle line:84%
about how prime numbers
are distributed modulo q.

00:01:16.570 --> 00:01:40.070 align:middle line:90%


00:01:40.070 --> 00:01:41.190 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:01:41.190 --> 00:01:54.590 align:middle line:84%
So let's say pi of N is the
number of primes up to N.

00:01:54.590 --> 00:01:58.130 align:middle line:84%
And then, we can look at the
modulo q for some choice q

00:01:58.130 --> 00:02:02.650 align:middle line:84%
and see how many of those
primes are in each moduli class.

00:02:02.650 --> 00:02:13.530 align:middle line:84%
So pi N, q, a is the number
of p prime, p less than

00:02:13.530 --> 00:02:16.670 align:middle line:84%
or equal to N. And
p equals a mod q.

00:02:16.670 --> 00:02:21.850 align:middle line:90%


00:02:21.850 --> 00:02:26.370 align:middle line:84%
Now some of these moduli classes
will be quite-- some of these

00:02:26.370 --> 00:02:28.570 align:middle line:90%
will be quite small.

00:02:28.570 --> 00:02:31.170 align:middle line:84%
If a and q have a common
factor, then there

00:02:31.170 --> 00:02:34.930 align:middle line:84%
will be only finitely many
primes in this moduli class.

00:02:34.930 --> 00:02:39.650 align:middle line:84%
So the main focus is on the ones
where the GCD of a and q is 1.

00:02:39.650 --> 00:02:43.220 align:middle line:90%
So focus on the case.

00:02:43.220 --> 00:02:46.210 align:middle line:90%


00:02:46.210 --> 00:02:49.610 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to write
it that a is in Zq star.

00:02:49.610 --> 00:02:53.610 align:middle line:84%
Zq star is the set of
a and Z mod q, where

00:02:53.610 --> 00:02:55.470 align:middle line:90%
a is relatively prime to q.

00:02:55.470 --> 00:02:59.120 align:middle line:90%


00:02:59.120 --> 00:03:04.620 align:middle line:84%
So numerically
and theoretically,

00:03:04.620 --> 00:03:06.640 align:middle line:84%
it looks like the
primes are pretty evenly

00:03:06.640 --> 00:03:10.160 align:middle line:84%
distributed among all of
these residue classes.

00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:13.420 align:middle line:84%
And it is relevant to
say how many there are,

00:03:13.420 --> 00:03:16.740 align:middle line:90%
so that's called phi of q.

00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:20.480 align:middle line:84%
It's the cardinality of Zq star,
the number of different a that

00:03:20.480 --> 00:03:24.300 align:middle line:90%
are relatively prime to q.

00:03:24.300 --> 00:03:27.120 align:middle line:84%
So if the primes were really
well evenly distributed

00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:30.786 align:middle line:84%
among the moduli classes,
then you would expect--

00:03:30.786 --> 00:03:32.220 align:middle line:90%
so I'll write this way.

00:03:32.220 --> 00:03:37.480 align:middle line:84%
So we see even
distribution, and that

00:03:37.480 --> 00:03:42.800 align:middle line:84%
means that the actual number
of primes in the moduli class

00:03:42.800 --> 00:03:46.640 align:middle line:84%
is close to the total
number of primes

00:03:46.640 --> 00:03:49.030 align:middle line:84%
divided by the number
of moduli classes.

00:03:49.030 --> 00:03:53.040 align:middle line:90%


00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:59.060 align:middle line:84%
So how would we
measure this precisely?

00:03:59.060 --> 00:04:05.420 align:middle line:84%
We define delta q of N, the
defect of equidistribution,

00:04:05.420 --> 00:04:08.300 align:middle line:84%
to be the maximum
over all the residue

00:04:08.300 --> 00:04:12.100 align:middle line:84%
classes of the difference
between the actual number

00:04:12.100 --> 00:04:15.640 align:middle line:84%
of primes and this
naive estimate.

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:22.600 align:middle line:90%


00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:25.180 align:middle line:84%
So when we ask, how
evenly are primes

00:04:25.180 --> 00:04:28.140 align:middle line:84%
distributed modulo q,
quantitatively, that means,

00:04:28.140 --> 00:04:29.360 align:middle line:90%
how big is this thing?

00:04:29.360 --> 00:04:32.140 align:middle line:90%


00:04:32.140 --> 00:04:34.700 align:middle line:84%
So this question
was first addressed

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:38.540 align:middle line:84%
by Dirichlet, who showed
that, in a certain sense,

00:04:38.540 --> 00:04:41.020 align:middle line:90%
that this is close to this.

00:04:41.020 --> 00:04:41.950 align:middle line:90%
Here's what he proved.

00:04:41.950 --> 00:04:49.100 align:middle line:90%


00:04:49.100 --> 00:04:53.140 align:middle line:84%
He proved that for any q, if
you take the limit as N goes

00:04:53.140 --> 00:04:59.450 align:middle line:84%
to infinity of
delta q of N, it's

00:04:59.450 --> 00:05:02.930 align:middle line:90%
asymptotically smaller than N/q.

00:05:02.930 --> 00:05:04.350 align:middle line:90%
So this limit is 0.

00:05:04.350 --> 00:05:08.710 align:middle line:90%


00:05:08.710 --> 00:05:10.210 align:middle line:84%
So actually, let
me say, when you're

00:05:10.210 --> 00:05:12.330 align:middle line:84%
talking about these
being equidistributed,

00:05:12.330 --> 00:05:14.290 align:middle line:84%
we're going to mean
that this is small.

00:05:14.290 --> 00:05:16.490 align:middle line:90%
Small relative to what?

00:05:16.490 --> 00:05:21.570 align:middle line:84%
Well, this is a good
approximation of this

00:05:21.570 --> 00:05:26.010 align:middle line:84%
if this error term is small
compared to the main term.

00:05:26.010 --> 00:05:33.650 align:middle line:84%
So equidistribution would
mean that delta q of N

00:05:33.650 --> 00:05:36.050 align:middle line:84%
is much smaller than
the main term, which

00:05:36.050 --> 00:05:44.782 align:middle line:84%
is on the order of N/q, or
it could be N over log N q.

00:05:44.782 --> 00:05:48.090 align:middle line:90%


00:05:48.090 --> 00:05:54.530 align:middle line:84%
So Dirichlet's arguments, you
can make them quantitative.

00:05:54.530 --> 00:05:56.030 align:middle line:84%
Instead of having
a limit, you could

00:05:56.030 --> 00:05:58.870 align:middle line:90%
say, if N is sufficiently big.

00:05:58.870 --> 00:06:02.510 align:middle line:84%
And they were made quantitative
by Siegel and Walfisz, which

00:06:02.510 --> 00:06:03.900 align:middle line:90%
involves some additional ideas.

00:06:03.900 --> 00:06:08.670 align:middle line:90%


00:06:08.670 --> 00:06:12.750 align:middle line:84%
And so this line of thinking
led to the following theorem.

00:06:12.750 --> 00:06:20.190 align:middle line:84%
So for any q, delta q
of N is bounded by--

00:06:20.190 --> 00:06:21.810 align:middle line:90%
OK, so let me say it this way.

00:06:21.810 --> 00:06:27.710 align:middle line:84%
So for any A, there's a constant
C sub A. And delta q of N

00:06:27.710 --> 00:06:40.122 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by C sub A, N,
log of N to the minus A.

00:06:40.122 --> 00:06:41.570 align:middle line:90%
Now when is this useful?

00:06:41.570 --> 00:06:43.430 align:middle line:84%
When does this tell
us that delta q of N

00:06:43.430 --> 00:06:45.470 align:middle line:90%
is much smaller than N/q?

00:06:45.470 --> 00:06:48.750 align:middle line:90%
Well, q cannot be too big.

00:06:48.750 --> 00:06:53.860 align:middle line:84%
So delta q N is much
smaller than N/q

00:06:53.860 --> 00:07:05.157 align:middle line:84%
if q is smaller than
a power of log N.

00:07:05.157 --> 00:07:06.740 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to
talk about the proofs

00:07:06.740 --> 00:07:09.420 align:middle line:90%
of these theorems in the class.

00:07:09.420 --> 00:07:10.907 align:middle line:84%
So Dirichlet
invented L-functions,

00:07:10.907 --> 00:07:12.740 align:middle line:84%
you may have heard of
Dirichlet L-functions,

00:07:12.740 --> 00:07:14.580 align:middle line:90%
in order to prove this theorem.

00:07:14.580 --> 00:07:17.040 align:middle line:84%
And all of this work is
based on L-functions.

00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:22.500 align:middle line:90%


00:07:22.500 --> 00:07:28.260 align:middle line:84%
So those are nice
theorems, but they only

00:07:28.260 --> 00:07:31.620 align:middle line:84%
work when q is pretty
small compared to N.

00:07:31.620 --> 00:07:34.100 align:middle line:90%
What happens if q is bigger?

00:07:34.100 --> 00:07:38.180 align:middle line:84%
Well, experimentally what seems
to happen is the following.

00:07:38.180 --> 00:07:40.600 align:middle line:84%
So this is conjectured
by Montgomery.

00:07:40.600 --> 00:07:43.820 align:middle line:90%


00:07:43.820 --> 00:07:48.900 align:middle line:84%
So for every epsilon
bigger than 0, delta q of N

00:07:48.900 --> 00:07:52.300 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by C epsilon
N to the epsilon.

00:07:52.300 --> 00:07:53.880 align:middle line:90%
It's like a fudge factor.

00:07:53.880 --> 00:07:57.200 align:middle line:84%
And then, there's
N/q to the 1/2.

00:07:57.200 --> 00:08:00.720 align:middle line:90%


00:08:00.720 --> 00:08:03.400 align:middle line:84%
So this is a
pseudorandom behavior.

00:08:03.400 --> 00:08:07.600 align:middle line:84%
So a good reference point,
sometimes people ask,

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:08.880 align:middle line:90%
are primes distributed?

00:08:08.880 --> 00:08:11.260 align:middle line:84%
Does it look random the
way primes are distributed?

00:08:11.260 --> 00:08:13.440 align:middle line:84%
So a good reference
point is there

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:16.720 align:middle line:84%
are about N over log N
primes up to N. So instead,

00:08:16.720 --> 00:08:19.240 align:middle line:84%
pick N over log
N random numbers.

00:08:19.240 --> 00:08:21.680 align:middle line:84%
Reduce the mod q and
see what happens.

00:08:21.680 --> 00:08:24.500 align:middle line:84%
So this is what you would see
if you had random numbers.

00:08:24.500 --> 00:08:29.360 align:middle line:84%
So this is a
pseudorandom conjecture.

00:08:29.360 --> 00:08:33.360 align:middle line:84%
So this is much stronger
than we could prove.

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:36.960 align:middle line:84%
And it implies, incidentally,
that delta q of N

00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:39.520 align:middle line:84%
is much smaller than N/q,
so we have some pretty good

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:43.120 align:middle line:84%
equidistribution, as long
as q is smaller than N

00:08:43.120 --> 00:08:45.560 align:middle line:90%
to the 1 minus epsilon.

00:08:45.560 --> 00:08:49.770 align:middle line:84%
So there is a huge gap
between this and this.

00:08:49.770 --> 00:08:55.750 align:middle line:90%


00:08:55.750 --> 00:08:58.510 align:middle line:84%
So this result, I think,
was proven in the 1930s.

00:08:58.510 --> 00:09:01.610 align:middle line:84%
And it is still, today, the
best result of its kind.

00:09:01.610 --> 00:09:05.400 align:middle line:84%
So we cannot increase this
to say N to the epsilon.

00:09:05.400 --> 00:09:08.150 align:middle line:90%


00:09:08.150 --> 00:09:10.630 align:middle line:84%
If we are willing to assume
the Riemann hypothesis,

00:09:10.630 --> 00:09:14.070 align:middle line:84%
or this would be the
generalized Riemann hypothesis,

00:09:14.070 --> 00:09:17.050 align:middle line:84%
then we get much
stronger information,

00:09:17.050 --> 00:09:19.230 align:middle line:84%
although still not
this conjecture.

00:09:19.230 --> 00:09:23.790 align:middle line:84%
So it says, for every
epsilon bigger than 0,

00:09:23.790 --> 00:09:29.190 align:middle line:84%
delta q of N is bounded by
C epsilon, N to the epsilon,

00:09:29.190 --> 00:09:31.510 align:middle line:90%
times N to the 1/2.

00:09:31.510 --> 00:09:35.390 align:middle line:84%
Looks like this, but with
no q in the denominator.

00:09:35.390 --> 00:09:38.750 align:middle line:84%
And that's good enough to
imply that we get some amount

00:09:38.750 --> 00:09:43.920 align:middle line:84%
of equidistribution if q is
smaller than N to the 1/2 minus

00:09:43.920 --> 00:09:44.420 align:middle line:90%
epsilon.

00:09:44.420 --> 00:09:53.490 align:middle line:90%


00:09:53.490 --> 00:09:57.450 align:middle line:84%
So it gives some idea of how
difficult this conjecture is

00:09:57.450 --> 00:09:59.190 align:middle line:84%
that, even with the
Riemann hypothesis,

00:09:59.190 --> 00:10:00.790 align:middle line:90%
we're only halfway there.

00:10:00.790 --> 00:10:05.890 align:middle line:90%


00:10:05.890 --> 00:10:07.910 align:middle line:84%
So this is everything
that is known

00:10:07.910 --> 00:10:10.090 align:middle line:84%
if you want to have a
theorem that definitely

00:10:10.090 --> 00:10:12.370 align:middle line:90%
works for a particular q.

00:10:12.370 --> 00:10:16.690 align:middle line:84%
And having run into
a barrier there

00:10:16.690 --> 00:10:19.810 align:middle line:84%
that has been difficult to
overcome, people started

00:10:19.810 --> 00:10:22.130 align:middle line:84%
to think about, well,
maybe we won't prove

00:10:22.130 --> 00:10:23.690 align:middle line:90%
a theorem for every single q.

00:10:23.690 --> 00:10:26.730 align:middle line:84%
But we could prove a
theorem for most of them.

00:10:26.730 --> 00:10:29.050 align:middle line:84%
So that's the main
topic of the class

00:10:29.050 --> 00:10:31.920 align:middle line:90%
today, so theorems for most q.

00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:35.250 align:middle line:90%


00:10:35.250 --> 00:10:39.850 align:middle line:84%
So this theorem, again,
I want to credit Rényi

00:10:39.850 --> 00:10:41.875 align:middle line:90%
and Bombieri-Vinogradov.

00:10:41.875 --> 00:10:46.680 align:middle line:90%


00:10:46.680 --> 00:10:49.200 align:middle line:84%
I read about the
history yesterday.

00:10:49.200 --> 00:10:52.600 align:middle line:84%
So this is usually called the
Bombieri-Vinogradov theorem.

00:10:52.600 --> 00:10:54.920 align:middle line:84%
The first person to prove
a theorem of this flavor

00:10:54.920 --> 00:10:56.140 align:middle line:90%
seems to be Rényi.

00:10:56.140 --> 00:10:58.400 align:middle line:84%
And then, various people
improved the parameters

00:10:58.400 --> 00:11:03.220 align:middle line:84%
in the theorem, building up
to Bombieri and Vinogradov.

00:11:03.220 --> 00:11:06.430 align:middle line:84%
So it says the following thing
for every epsilon bigger than 0.

00:11:06.430 --> 00:11:11.640 align:middle line:90%


00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:18.880 align:middle line:84%
So if I take the sum, epsilon q,
up to N to the 1/2 minus epsilon

00:11:18.880 --> 00:11:24.170 align:middle line:84%
of delta q of N, check
the exact phrasing.

00:11:24.170 --> 00:11:33.240 align:middle line:90%


00:11:33.240 --> 00:11:39.920 align:middle line:84%
A, then, this is
bounded by constant

00:11:39.920 --> 00:11:49.860 align:middle line:84%
depending on epsilon and A,
and log of N to the minus A.

00:11:49.860 --> 00:11:52.020 align:middle line:84%
So let's digest
this a little bit.

00:11:52.020 --> 00:11:55.300 align:middle line:84%
So the job of epsilon is
that we can almost go up to N

00:11:55.300 --> 00:11:58.900 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2, but not quite.

00:11:58.900 --> 00:12:02.410 align:middle line:90%
And then, the job of A is that--

00:12:02.410 --> 00:12:07.000 align:middle line:90%


00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:12.160 align:middle line:84%
so this tells us that
for most, not all,

00:12:12.160 --> 00:12:17.700 align:middle line:84%
but most of the q up to N
to the 1/2 minus epsilon,

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:20.420 align:middle line:84%
delta q of N is
bounded by, well,

00:12:20.420 --> 00:12:24.060 align:middle line:84%
I divide both sides by
the number of terms.

00:12:24.060 --> 00:12:30.260 align:middle line:84%
And so I could put here,
N/q log of N to the minus

00:12:30.260 --> 00:12:34.460 align:middle line:84%
A, so which is indeed
much smaller than N/q.

00:12:34.460 --> 00:12:38.860 align:middle line:84%
So informally, for most q,
we get good equidistribution

00:12:38.860 --> 00:12:40.840 align:middle line:90%
of the primes modulo q.

00:12:40.840 --> 00:12:54.570 align:middle line:90%


00:12:54.570 --> 00:12:59.810 align:middle line:84%
And it so happens that the size
of the q's we can get up to here

00:12:59.810 --> 00:13:02.290 align:middle line:84%
matches the size of the q's
you can get up to if you

00:13:02.290 --> 00:13:05.130 align:middle line:90%
knew the Riemann hypothesis.

00:13:05.130 --> 00:13:09.260 align:middle line:84%
And so this is sometimes
summarized as being,

00:13:09.260 --> 00:13:11.510 align:middle line:84%
it's definitely not as good
as the Riemann hypothesis,

00:13:11.510 --> 00:13:15.890 align:middle line:84%
but it's for most version
of what you would learn

00:13:15.890 --> 00:13:17.230 align:middle line:90%
from the Riemann hypothesis.

00:13:17.230 --> 00:13:31.930 align:middle line:90%


00:13:31.930 --> 00:13:37.450 align:middle line:84%
So my goal today is
to tell you the ideas

00:13:37.450 --> 00:13:38.803 align:middle line:90%
of the proof of this theorem.

00:13:38.803 --> 00:13:40.720 align:middle line:84%
There are certain things
that are a bit messy.

00:13:40.720 --> 00:13:42.345 align:middle line:84%
And I won't do all
of the messy things,

00:13:42.345 --> 00:13:44.720 align:middle line:90%
so we won't do a complete proof.

00:13:44.720 --> 00:13:46.920 align:middle line:84%
But I'd like to address
a couple of questions,

00:13:46.920 --> 00:13:49.360 align:middle line:84%
like, what does this have to
do with sieves and projection

00:13:49.360 --> 00:13:50.440 align:middle line:90%
theory?

00:13:50.440 --> 00:13:53.400 align:middle line:84%
And another question, what
does it have to do with primes,

00:13:53.400 --> 00:13:55.270 align:middle line:84%
or how will we use
it there, in primes?

00:13:55.270 --> 00:14:04.480 align:middle line:90%


00:14:04.480 --> 00:14:07.520 align:middle line:84%
Since we're only trying to
prove things for most q,

00:14:07.520 --> 00:14:10.018 align:middle line:84%
we're looking at all
of the different q's.

00:14:10.018 --> 00:14:12.560 align:middle line:84%
So we have one set of primes
and we're projecting it modulo q

00:14:12.560 --> 00:14:13.890 align:middle line:90%
for lots of different q's.

00:14:13.890 --> 00:14:15.640 align:middle line:84%
So that's the setting
of projection theory

00:14:15.640 --> 00:14:19.520 align:middle line:84%
where we can bring in
things like the large sieve.

00:14:19.520 --> 00:14:28.360 align:middle line:84%
So I wanted to recall,
so the large sieve

00:14:28.360 --> 00:14:30.800 align:middle line:84%
allows us to prove the
following kind of thing.

00:14:30.800 --> 00:14:34.760 align:middle line:84%
So we have a set x contained
in the integers up to N.

00:14:34.760 --> 00:14:38.520 align:middle line:90%
And I look at pi p of 1 x.

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:42.940 align:middle line:84%
And I'll take the
high part of that.

00:14:42.940 --> 00:14:52.600 align:middle line:84%
And then this thing is
small for most p in Pm.

00:14:52.600 --> 00:14:57.180 align:middle line:90%
So this Pm, maybe I'll put it--

00:14:57.180 --> 00:15:04.000 align:middle line:84%
so Pm is the set of
p prime, p around m.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:07.620 align:middle line:90%


00:15:07.620 --> 00:15:11.440 align:middle line:84%
So this looks, on the
surface, like a similar thing.

00:15:11.440 --> 00:15:13.020 align:middle line:90%
We have a set x.

00:15:13.020 --> 00:15:16.700 align:middle line:84%
We project it modulo p for
many different primes p.

00:15:16.700 --> 00:15:19.360 align:middle line:84%
And we throw out
the constant part

00:15:19.360 --> 00:15:21.980 align:middle line:84%
and just look at the
variation from being constant.

00:15:21.980 --> 00:15:24.420 align:middle line:84%
And this is saying that this
projection is pretty evenly

00:15:24.420 --> 00:15:29.500 align:middle line:84%
distributed for
most of the primes.

00:15:29.500 --> 00:15:30.840 align:middle line:90%
So it sounds similar to this.

00:15:30.840 --> 00:15:32.673 align:middle line:84%
And indeed, this will
be crucially relevant.

00:15:32.673 --> 00:15:35.060 align:middle line:90%


00:15:35.060 --> 00:15:40.397 align:middle line:84%
Now this is a statement
about every set x.

00:15:40.397 --> 00:15:42.230 align:middle line:84%
In particular, you could
put the primes here

00:15:42.230 --> 00:15:44.570 align:middle line:84%
so you get a theorem
about primes,

00:15:44.570 --> 00:15:47.290 align:middle line:90%
but it's true for every set.

00:15:47.290 --> 00:15:51.690 align:middle line:84%
This theorem is definitely
not true for every set.

00:15:51.690 --> 00:16:00.290 align:middle line:84%
So I'll make a remark that
the theorem is not true

00:16:00.290 --> 00:16:06.490 align:middle line:84%
if you replace the
primes by just some set

00:16:06.490 --> 00:16:10.090 align:middle line:84%
x of numbers up to
N, with maybe roughly

00:16:10.090 --> 00:16:11.380 align:middle line:90%
the same size as the primes.

00:16:11.380 --> 00:16:16.650 align:middle line:90%


00:16:16.650 --> 00:16:20.550 align:middle line:84%
So there's a simple example, but
I think it's instructive to see.

00:16:20.550 --> 00:16:24.290 align:middle line:90%


00:16:24.290 --> 00:16:25.850 align:middle line:84%
So the examples
like this, I'm going

00:16:25.850 --> 00:16:28.290 align:middle line:84%
to try to build
a set where I can

00:16:28.290 --> 00:16:30.250 align:middle line:90%
reduce it modulo every prime.

00:16:30.250 --> 00:16:33.410 align:middle line:84%
And whichever prime
I reduce it by,

00:16:33.410 --> 00:16:35.650 align:middle line:84%
I will see one
moduli class which

00:16:35.650 --> 00:16:38.590 align:middle line:90%
is extremely overrepresented.

00:16:38.590 --> 00:16:40.990 align:middle line:84%
So here's how we
build such a set.

00:16:40.990 --> 00:16:44.430 align:middle line:84%
So for every p in primes
of size around m, m

00:16:44.430 --> 00:16:52.710 align:middle line:84%
is just a free parameter here,
I choose some a and Z mod p.

00:16:52.710 --> 00:16:56.030 align:middle line:84%
And then, I'll make my
set x is going to be

00:16:56.030 --> 00:16:58.710 align:middle line:90%
the union over all the primes.

00:16:58.710 --> 00:17:04.270 align:middle line:84%
And then, I take
the set of N up to N

00:17:04.270 --> 00:17:06.650 align:middle line:90%
so that N is equal to a mod p.

00:17:06.650 --> 00:17:09.390 align:middle line:90%


00:17:09.390 --> 00:17:12.150 align:middle line:84%
So for each prime I
pick a moduli class.

00:17:12.150 --> 00:17:15.310 align:middle line:84%
I take all the integers
in that moduli class,

00:17:15.310 --> 00:17:18.379 align:middle line:84%
and I take a union over all
the primes in my set of primes.

00:17:18.379 --> 00:17:22.750 align:middle line:90%


00:17:22.750 --> 00:17:29.750 align:middle line:84%
So if I were to
take pi p1x of a,

00:17:29.750 --> 00:17:33.150 align:middle line:84%
well, x contains
all the integers

00:17:33.150 --> 00:17:36.220 align:middle line:84%
in this moduli class up
to N. So this is basically

00:17:36.220 --> 00:17:38.420 align:middle line:90%
N/p, which is around N/m.

00:17:38.420 --> 00:17:42.540 align:middle line:90%


00:17:42.540 --> 00:17:44.400 align:middle line:84%
And that's much
bigger than average.

00:17:44.400 --> 00:17:47.860 align:middle line:90%


00:17:47.860 --> 00:17:49.800 align:middle line:84%
The average would be
the size of-- yes.

00:17:49.800 --> 00:17:52.020 align:middle line:84%
So actually, let's
figure out the size of x.

00:17:52.020 --> 00:17:59.940 align:middle line:84%
So the size of x is, at most,
there will be about N/m numbers

00:17:59.940 --> 00:18:03.660 align:middle line:90%
in this moduli class.

00:18:03.660 --> 00:18:08.980 align:middle line:84%
And then, there are about
M over log m primes,

00:18:08.980 --> 00:18:10.090 align:middle line:90%
so something like this.

00:18:10.090 --> 00:18:15.340 align:middle line:90%


00:18:15.340 --> 00:18:17.920 align:middle line:90%
So that is a smallish fraction.

00:18:17.920 --> 00:18:20.620 align:middle line:90%
It's much less than all of them.

00:18:20.620 --> 00:18:25.900 align:middle line:84%
So this is way smaller
than the size of x over p.

00:18:25.900 --> 00:18:28.940 align:middle line:84%
So this guy is seriously
overrepresented,

00:18:28.940 --> 00:18:30.520 align:middle line:90%
and it happens for every p.

00:18:30.520 --> 00:18:36.200 align:middle line:90%


00:18:36.200 --> 00:18:37.240 align:middle line:90%
OK, great.

00:18:37.240 --> 00:18:42.800 align:middle line:84%
So this theorem is, we
will see, the large sieve

00:18:42.800 --> 00:18:44.660 align:middle line:84%
is absolutely crucial
thing in the proof.

00:18:44.660 --> 00:18:45.680 align:middle line:90%
It's the main idea.

00:18:45.680 --> 00:18:47.980 align:middle line:84%
But this is not a theorem
about arbitrary sets.

00:18:47.980 --> 00:18:50.240 align:middle line:84%
It's a theorem
about prime numbers,

00:18:50.240 --> 00:18:54.030 align:middle line:84%
and so the proof needs to use
something about prime numbers.

00:18:54.030 --> 00:18:59.800 align:middle line:90%


00:18:59.800 --> 00:19:04.960 align:middle line:84%
So the main character
is a concept called

00:19:04.960 --> 00:19:07.480 align:middle line:90%
multiplicative convolution.

00:19:07.480 --> 00:19:10.300 align:middle line:84%
And I think this is a nice
concept to know about.

00:19:10.300 --> 00:19:12.880 align:middle line:84%
It's a cousin of regular
additive convolution.

00:19:12.880 --> 00:19:15.480 align:middle line:90%


00:19:15.480 --> 00:19:18.820 align:middle line:84%
We'll see that it interacts with
all the things in our story.

00:19:18.820 --> 00:19:21.440 align:middle line:84%
So multiplicative
convolution interacts really

00:19:21.440 --> 00:19:24.080 align:middle line:84%
nicely with prime
numbers, describing

00:19:24.080 --> 00:19:27.360 align:middle line:84%
what our prime numbers,
it comes up naturally.

00:19:27.360 --> 00:19:30.360 align:middle line:84%
And it also interacts nicely
with taking projections.

00:19:30.360 --> 00:19:32.830 align:middle line:84%
And so it interacts nicely
with the large sieve,

00:19:32.830 --> 00:19:35.850 align:middle line:84%
and fitting all those things
together is how we prove this.

00:19:35.850 --> 00:19:43.690 align:middle line:90%


00:19:43.690 --> 00:19:45.650 align:middle line:84%
So what is multiplicative
convolution?

00:19:45.650 --> 00:19:58.750 align:middle line:90%


00:19:58.750 --> 00:20:04.830 align:middle line:84%
So suppose f and g are functions
on the natural numbers.

00:20:04.830 --> 00:20:09.110 align:middle line:84%
If I take the multiplicative
convolution of them,

00:20:09.110 --> 00:20:13.270 align:middle line:84%
it means I add up over
all the pairs n1 and n2

00:20:13.270 --> 00:20:15.070 align:middle line:90%
whose product is n.

00:20:15.070 --> 00:20:19.010 align:middle line:84%
And then, I take
f of n1, g of n2.

00:20:19.010 --> 00:20:23.390 align:middle line:90%


00:20:23.390 --> 00:20:25.570 align:middle line:84%
So let's compare that
with regular convolution.

00:20:25.570 --> 00:20:28.390 align:middle line:84%
So regular convolution,
say, on the integers,

00:20:28.390 --> 00:20:29.730 align:middle line:90%
would be the same thing.

00:20:29.730 --> 00:20:32.970 align:middle line:84%
But I would have the sum
over all the pairs n1 n2 who

00:20:32.970 --> 00:20:33.770 align:middle line:90%
add up to n.

00:20:33.770 --> 00:20:37.250 align:middle line:84%
And the multiplicative version
is, we replace the sum here

00:20:37.250 --> 00:20:37.860 align:middle line:90%
by a product.

00:20:37.860 --> 00:20:41.930 align:middle line:90%


00:20:41.930 --> 00:20:43.750 align:middle line:84%
So that's multiplicative
convolution.

00:20:43.750 --> 00:20:51.810 align:middle line:90%


00:20:51.810 --> 00:20:58.210 align:middle line:84%
So we have to see how
multiplicative convolution

00:20:58.210 --> 00:21:01.490 align:middle line:90%
connects with primes.

00:21:01.490 --> 00:21:05.850 align:middle line:84%
And we have to see how
multiplicative convolution

00:21:05.850 --> 00:21:07.710 align:middle line:90%
interacts with projections.

00:21:07.710 --> 00:21:10.530 align:middle line:90%


00:21:10.530 --> 00:21:14.530 align:middle line:84%
We'll put that together and
that's how we prove the theorem.

00:21:14.530 --> 00:21:16.180 align:middle line:90%
So let's start with primes.

00:21:16.180 --> 00:21:28.330 align:middle line:90%


00:21:28.330 --> 00:21:35.440 align:middle line:84%
So the large sieve inequality,
we use this word, sieve.

00:21:35.440 --> 00:21:41.080 align:middle line:84%
And I will explain
to you now, where

00:21:41.080 --> 00:21:43.158 align:middle line:90%
does the word sieve come from?

00:21:43.158 --> 00:21:45.450 align:middle line:84%
And it comes out naturally
when you think about primes.

00:21:45.450 --> 00:21:56.680 align:middle line:90%


00:21:56.680 --> 00:22:01.900 align:middle line:84%
So how do you find
the prime numbers?

00:22:01.900 --> 00:22:04.300 align:middle line:84%
Suppose I wanted to make a
list of prime numbers up to n.

00:22:04.300 --> 00:22:05.420 align:middle line:90%
What would I do?

00:22:05.420 --> 00:22:07.520 align:middle line:84%
I would start with all
the natural numbers.

00:22:07.520 --> 00:22:09.880 align:middle line:84%
Then, I cross off
the multiples of two.

00:22:09.880 --> 00:22:12.500 align:middle line:84%
Then, I cross off the
multiples of 3, and so on.

00:22:12.500 --> 00:22:14.530 align:middle line:84%
And then, what's left
are the prime numbers.

00:22:14.530 --> 00:22:17.080 align:middle line:90%


00:22:17.080 --> 00:22:18.690 align:middle line:84%
So that process
is called sieving.

00:22:18.690 --> 00:22:21.760 align:middle line:90%


00:22:21.760 --> 00:22:23.400 align:middle line:84%
I think sieving
physically is where

00:22:23.400 --> 00:22:28.180 align:middle line:84%
you take a thing full of
sand that somewhere in there

00:22:28.180 --> 00:22:30.320 align:middle line:84%
has a little gold, or
diamond, or something.

00:22:30.320 --> 00:22:31.900 align:middle line:84%
And you shake this
thing and the sand

00:22:31.900 --> 00:22:33.317 align:middle line:84%
falls out, until
eventually you're

00:22:33.317 --> 00:22:34.900 align:middle line:90%
just left with the diamonds.

00:22:34.900 --> 00:22:37.300 align:middle line:84%
So the image is you have a
thing full of sand, which

00:22:37.300 --> 00:22:38.490 align:middle line:90%
are all the natural numbers.

00:22:38.490 --> 00:22:40.740 align:middle line:84%
And you shake it, and you
take out the multiples of 2,

00:22:40.740 --> 00:22:42.000 align:middle line:84%
and the multiples
of 3, or whatever.

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:44.380 align:middle line:84%
And then, eventually you just
have the prime numbers left.

00:22:44.380 --> 00:22:45.088 align:middle line:90%
That's the image.

00:22:45.088 --> 00:22:54.500 align:middle line:90%


00:22:54.500 --> 00:23:00.420 align:middle line:84%
To find the primes, we start
with the natural numbers.

00:23:00.420 --> 00:23:06.540 align:middle line:84%
Then, we cross out
multiples of 2.

00:23:06.540 --> 00:23:14.380 align:middle line:84%
Then, we cross out multiples
of 3, and dot, dot, dot.

00:23:14.380 --> 00:23:16.080 align:middle line:90%
So we can all imagine that.

00:23:16.080 --> 00:23:19.200 align:middle line:84%
Now, let's try to describe
this process using formulas.

00:23:19.200 --> 00:23:21.500 align:middle line:84%
And we'll see that the
formulas that naturally appear

00:23:21.500 --> 00:23:25.580 align:middle line:84%
are formulas involving
multiplicative convolution.

00:23:25.580 --> 00:23:31.250 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to write 1 of n to
be the characteristic function

00:23:31.250 --> 00:23:34.570 align:middle line:90%
of all the natural numbers.

00:23:34.570 --> 00:23:37.010 align:middle line:84%
And then, the next
character I'm going to put

00:23:37.010 --> 00:23:42.410 align:middle line:84%
is a function called
difference sub p of n.

00:23:42.410 --> 00:23:49.490 align:middle line:84%
So it's 1 if n equals 1, and
it's negative 1 if n is p,

00:23:49.490 --> 00:23:51.030 align:middle line:90%
and it's 0 otherwise.

00:23:51.030 --> 00:23:54.090 align:middle line:90%


00:23:54.090 --> 00:23:57.290 align:middle line:84%
Now let's think
what would happen

00:23:57.290 --> 00:23:59.650 align:middle line:84%
if I took all the
natural numbers

00:23:59.650 --> 00:24:02.210 align:middle line:84%
and I did a multiplicative
convolution with D2.

00:24:02.210 --> 00:24:06.730 align:middle line:90%


00:24:06.730 --> 00:24:12.330 align:middle line:84%
So this would give me, so D2 has
a positive delta function at 1

00:24:12.330 --> 00:24:15.370 align:middle line:84%
and a negative
delta function at 2.

00:24:15.370 --> 00:24:19.610 align:middle line:84%
So when I do this I'm going
to get characteristic function

00:24:19.610 --> 00:24:22.450 align:middle line:84%
of all the natural numbers
coming from this 1,

00:24:22.450 --> 00:24:25.470 align:middle line:84%
minus the characteristic
function of 2 times

00:24:25.470 --> 00:24:27.890 align:middle line:84%
the natural numbers
coming from that 1.

00:24:27.890 --> 00:24:33.590 align:middle line:90%


00:24:33.590 --> 00:24:34.390 align:middle line:90%
Let me pause there.

00:24:34.390 --> 00:24:35.530 align:middle line:90%
Does that make sense?

00:24:35.530 --> 00:24:38.150 align:middle line:84%
Does that fit with the
plugging in the definition

00:24:38.150 --> 00:24:41.350 align:middle line:90%
of multiplicative convolution?

00:24:41.350 --> 00:24:43.230 align:middle line:90%
Let's do it slowly to be sure.

00:24:43.230 --> 00:24:45.190 align:middle line:90%
So what's the definition?

00:24:45.190 --> 00:24:51.230 align:middle line:84%
1 convolved with
D2 of n is the sum.

00:24:51.230 --> 00:24:58.900 align:middle line:84%
n1, n2 equals n of 1
of n1 times D2 of n2.

00:24:58.900 --> 00:25:02.670 align:middle line:90%


00:25:02.670 --> 00:25:06.690 align:middle line:84%
Now D2 is only
non-vanishing in two cases.

00:25:06.690 --> 00:25:09.830 align:middle line:84%
So we actually only have
to consider that n2 is 1

00:25:09.830 --> 00:25:12.750 align:middle line:90%
or n2 is 2.

00:25:12.750 --> 00:25:16.470 align:middle line:90%
So the 1 is always there.

00:25:16.470 --> 00:25:22.230 align:middle line:90%
So that is 1 of n times D2 of 1.

00:25:22.230 --> 00:25:29.480 align:middle line:84%
And then, if D is even, so this
is what happens if n is odd.

00:25:29.480 --> 00:25:32.460 align:middle line:90%


00:25:32.460 --> 00:25:37.360 align:middle line:84%
And then, if n is even,
then n2 could be 2.

00:25:37.360 --> 00:25:40.900 align:middle line:84%
So we would get 1
of n, 1 of n over 2.

00:25:40.900 --> 00:25:43.380 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, we get the--

00:25:43.380 --> 00:25:44.820 align:middle line:90%
so this is both cases.

00:25:44.820 --> 00:25:54.540 align:middle line:84%
1 of n, D2 of 1, minus 1 of
plus 1 of n over 2, D2 of 2.

00:25:54.540 --> 00:25:56.100 align:middle line:90%
So this is just 1.

00:25:56.100 --> 00:25:58.623 align:middle line:84%
And this is 1 minus
1, which is 0.

00:25:58.623 --> 00:26:00.540 align:middle line:84%
So we're left with the
characteristic function

00:26:00.540 --> 00:26:03.980 align:middle line:90%
of the odd numbers.

00:26:03.980 --> 00:26:05.540 align:middle line:90%
Let's go one further.

00:26:05.540 --> 00:26:08.340 align:middle line:84%
If I take the characteristic
function of the naturals,

00:26:08.340 --> 00:26:11.100 align:middle line:84%
I do a multiplicative
convolution with D2.

00:26:11.100 --> 00:26:15.620 align:middle line:84%
Then, I do a multiplicative
convolution with D3.

00:26:15.620 --> 00:26:16.560 align:middle line:90%
What happens?

00:26:16.560 --> 00:26:19.100 align:middle line:84%
Well, this 1 gives me the
characteristic function

00:26:19.100 --> 00:26:20.780 align:middle line:90%
of the odd numbers.

00:26:20.780 --> 00:26:22.410 align:middle line:90%
And then I'm convolving with D3.

00:26:22.410 --> 00:26:25.200 align:middle line:90%


00:26:25.200 --> 00:26:27.000 align:middle line:90%
Now what happens?

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:28.600 align:middle line:84%
I get the
characteristic function

00:26:28.600 --> 00:26:31.840 align:middle line:84%
of the odd numbers minus
the characteristic function

00:26:31.840 --> 00:26:34.680 align:middle line:90%
of 3 times the odd numbers.

00:26:34.680 --> 00:26:35.660 align:middle line:90%
Then, I do this.

00:26:35.660 --> 00:26:41.200 align:middle line:90%


00:26:41.200 --> 00:26:43.320 align:middle line:84%
So I have the odd
numbers, but now I'm

00:26:43.320 --> 00:26:47.560 align:middle line:84%
going to cross out the ones
that are multiples of 3.

00:26:47.560 --> 00:26:51.400 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
characteristic function of,

00:26:51.400 --> 00:26:56.790 align:middle line:84%
n is relatively
prime to 2 and 3.

00:26:56.790 --> 00:27:01.280 align:middle line:90%


00:27:01.280 --> 00:27:04.920 align:middle line:84%
So this shows by example
that this process, starting

00:27:04.920 --> 00:27:07.300 align:middle line:84%
with the natural numbers,
crossing out multiples of 2,

00:27:07.300 --> 00:27:10.640 align:middle line:84%
crossing out multiples of 3,
it corresponds to convolving

00:27:10.640 --> 00:27:13.100 align:middle line:90%
by these D's over and over.

00:27:13.100 --> 00:27:18.428 align:middle line:90%


00:27:18.428 --> 00:27:19.970 align:middle line:84%
So now let me make
a little notation.

00:27:19.970 --> 00:27:40.630 align:middle line:90%


00:27:40.630 --> 00:27:44.280 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to do sieve
for primes, general version.

00:27:44.280 --> 00:27:52.690 align:middle line:90%


00:27:52.690 --> 00:27:55.580 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that S
is a set of primes.

00:27:55.580 --> 00:27:58.110 align:middle line:90%


00:27:58.110 --> 00:28:01.830 align:middle line:84%
And then, RP sub s
of n, that stands

00:28:01.830 --> 00:28:05.150 align:middle line:90%
for relatively prime to s.

00:28:05.150 --> 00:28:13.010 align:middle line:84%
This is 1 if p and n are
relatively prime for all

00:28:13.010 --> 00:28:14.870 align:middle line:90%
the primes in my set.

00:28:14.870 --> 00:28:18.780 align:middle line:84%
So it's 1 if my number n is
relatively prime to everybody

00:28:18.780 --> 00:28:21.700 align:middle line:90%
in s, and 0 otherwise.

00:28:21.700 --> 00:28:26.680 align:middle line:84%
So it's 0 if there exists a
prime in my set that divides it.

00:28:26.680 --> 00:28:34.080 align:middle line:90%


00:28:34.080 --> 00:28:37.300 align:middle line:90%
So let's make our remark.

00:28:37.300 --> 00:28:43.060 align:middle line:84%
So if S is the primes that go
up to the square root of N,

00:28:43.060 --> 00:28:47.260 align:middle line:84%
and little n is,
let's say, bigger

00:28:47.260 --> 00:28:49.340 align:middle line:84%
than the square root
of N, but at most

00:28:49.340 --> 00:28:55.900 align:middle line:84%
N, then either n has a
prime factor from this list

00:28:55.900 --> 00:28:58.100 align:middle line:90%
or it is prime.

00:28:58.100 --> 00:29:06.300 align:middle line:84%
So in that case, our relatively
prime s of n is just P of n

00:29:06.300 --> 00:29:09.660 align:middle line:90%
whether n is prime.

00:29:09.660 --> 00:29:13.700 align:middle line:84%
So this thing, if I'm
interested in the primes

00:29:13.700 --> 00:29:15.940 align:middle line:84%
in a certain range,
say, from n over 2 to n,

00:29:15.940 --> 00:29:19.560 align:middle line:84%
I can detect them
using this function.

00:29:19.560 --> 00:29:23.480 align:middle line:84%
And this function we've just
seen is a big convolution.

00:29:23.480 --> 00:29:34.520 align:middle line:84%
So lemma, so if my set
of primes is p1 up to pr,

00:29:34.520 --> 00:29:41.800 align:middle line:84%
then relatively prime
sub s of n is 1 convolved

00:29:41.800 --> 00:29:46.360 align:middle line:90%
with Dp1, convolved with Dpr.

00:29:46.360 --> 00:29:48.980 align:middle line:84%
These are all
multiplicative convolutions.

00:29:48.980 --> 00:30:03.560 align:middle line:90%


00:30:03.560 --> 00:30:07.590 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Can I ask you,
for the examples there,

00:30:07.590 --> 00:30:14.360 align:middle line:84%
I wondered why you have
p of 1x of a is over p,

00:30:14.360 --> 00:30:23.570 align:middle line:84%
like why it really becomes
contributions from other teams?

00:30:23.570 --> 00:30:24.570 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah, OK.

00:30:24.570 --> 00:30:27.310 align:middle line:84%
So the question is coming
back to this example.

00:30:27.310 --> 00:30:31.470 align:middle line:84%
We built a set whose
projection onto every prime

00:30:31.470 --> 00:30:33.170 align:middle line:90%
has one place that's really big.

00:30:33.170 --> 00:30:36.270 align:middle line:90%


00:30:36.270 --> 00:30:41.390 align:middle line:84%
And x is made as a union
of arithmetic progressions.

00:30:41.390 --> 00:30:43.130 align:middle line:90%
Now this x is a set.

00:30:43.130 --> 00:30:44.290 align:middle line:90%
It's not a function.

00:30:44.290 --> 00:30:47.830 align:middle line:84%
So these arithmetic
progressions might overlap.

00:30:47.830 --> 00:30:52.070 align:middle line:84%
But if they do, the point where
they overlap in this formulation

00:30:52.070 --> 00:30:55.850 align:middle line:84%
only counts once, although
it's not super important.

00:30:55.850 --> 00:31:02.670 align:middle line:84%
So if you look at pi p of 1x of
a, that's how many elements of x

00:31:02.670 --> 00:31:05.750 align:middle line:90%
are congruent to a mod p.

00:31:05.750 --> 00:31:09.430 align:middle line:90%
And so all of them are already.

00:31:09.430 --> 00:31:11.390 align:middle line:84%
And some of the
other p might also

00:31:11.390 --> 00:31:14.290 align:middle line:84%
contain some of these elements,
but it doesn't count anymore.

00:31:14.290 --> 00:31:16.750 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Oh, OK.

00:31:16.750 --> 00:31:18.750 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Although
if it did count anymore,

00:31:18.750 --> 00:31:21.330 align:middle line:84%
it would just make this
phenomenon even more extreme

00:31:21.330 --> 00:31:22.350 align:middle line:90%
than it already is.

00:31:22.350 --> 00:31:29.410 align:middle line:90%


00:31:29.410 --> 00:31:30.730 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:31:30.730 --> 00:31:32.100 align:middle line:90%
Any other questions or comments?

00:31:32.100 --> 00:31:42.590 align:middle line:90%


00:31:42.590 --> 00:31:45.970 align:middle line:84%
So the characteristic
function of the primes

00:31:45.970 --> 00:31:48.630 align:middle line:84%
is a special function,
probably in lots of ways.

00:31:48.630 --> 00:31:50.650 align:middle line:84%
And the way that's
relevant for us today

00:31:50.650 --> 00:31:52.890 align:middle line:84%
is that the characteristic
function of the primes

00:31:52.890 --> 00:31:54.890 align:middle line:84%
is basically this
function, which

00:31:54.890 --> 00:31:58.170 align:middle line:84%
is a big convolution, a big
multiplicative convolution.

00:31:58.170 --> 00:32:01.490 align:middle line:84%
And so the
Bombieri-Vinogradov theorem

00:32:01.490 --> 00:32:04.850 align:middle line:84%
is mostly a theorem
about functions

00:32:04.850 --> 00:32:07.990 align:middle line:84%
that have the structure
that they're convolutions.

00:32:07.990 --> 00:32:13.360 align:middle line:90%


00:32:13.360 --> 00:32:15.560 align:middle line:84%
So that is how
multiplicative convolution

00:32:15.560 --> 00:32:17.720 align:middle line:90%
is related to primes.

00:32:17.720 --> 00:32:20.320 align:middle line:84%
Next, let's think about how
multiplicative convolution

00:32:20.320 --> 00:32:22.180 align:middle line:90%
is related to projections.

00:32:22.180 --> 00:33:09.785 align:middle line:90%


00:33:09.785 --> 00:33:14.390 align:middle line:84%
So here there are a bunch of
different fairly simple lemmas.

00:33:14.390 --> 00:33:21.020 align:middle line:90%


00:33:21.020 --> 00:33:27.220 align:middle line:84%
And all these lemmas
have the flavor

00:33:27.220 --> 00:33:28.940 align:middle line:84%
that doing multiplicative
convolution

00:33:28.940 --> 00:33:31.220 align:middle line:84%
and doing projections
fits together

00:33:31.220 --> 00:33:33.300 align:middle line:90%
as well as you could hope.

00:33:33.300 --> 00:33:35.140 align:middle line:84%
And I think, basically,
the reason for that

00:33:35.140 --> 00:33:37.460 align:middle line:84%
is that the projection
operation is

00:33:37.460 --> 00:33:43.100 align:middle line:84%
a ring homomorphism from the
ring Z to the ring Z mod q.

00:33:43.100 --> 00:33:45.080 align:middle line:84%
And we'll be talking
about multiplication.

00:33:45.080 --> 00:33:48.700 align:middle line:84%
So being a ring homomorphism,
it means that the projection

00:33:48.700 --> 00:33:51.980 align:middle line:90%
respects the product operation.

00:33:51.980 --> 00:33:54.500 align:middle line:84%
And so the multiplicative
convolution

00:33:54.500 --> 00:33:57.200 align:middle line:84%
is defined in terms of
the product operation,

00:33:57.200 --> 00:33:59.900 align:middle line:90%
so it all fits together.

00:33:59.900 --> 00:34:05.460 align:middle line:84%
So lemma 1 says that, if
f and g natural numbers

00:34:05.460 --> 00:34:13.850 align:middle line:84%
go to C, then if I take the
projection of f convolved

00:34:13.850 --> 00:34:19.170 align:middle line:84%
with g, I get the
projection of f convolved

00:34:19.170 --> 00:34:22.190 align:middle line:90%
with the projection of g.

00:34:22.190 --> 00:34:26.570 align:middle line:90%


00:34:26.570 --> 00:34:29.889 align:middle line:84%
This one requires
the definition.

00:34:29.889 --> 00:34:32.170 align:middle line:84%
If I had been
savvy in general, I

00:34:32.170 --> 00:34:35.290 align:middle line:84%
might have defined
multiplicative convolution

00:34:35.290 --> 00:34:39.570 align:middle line:84%
in the first place for
any multiplicative monoid

00:34:39.570 --> 00:34:41.370 align:middle line:90%
or something.

00:34:41.370 --> 00:34:44.846 align:middle line:84%
But anyway, let's just say
what it is for z mod q.

00:34:44.846 --> 00:34:45.679 align:middle line:90%
It is what we think.

00:34:45.679 --> 00:34:51.290 align:middle line:90%


00:34:51.290 --> 00:34:57.810 align:middle line:84%
If I have maybe capital F and
capital G functions on Z mod q,

00:34:57.810 --> 00:35:02.850 align:middle line:84%
then multiplicative
convolution of a class a

00:35:02.850 --> 00:35:06.610 align:middle line:84%
is the sum over all
pairs a1 a2 that

00:35:06.610 --> 00:35:14.410 align:middle line:84%
multiply to a of capital
F of a1, capital G of a2.

00:35:14.410 --> 00:35:20.430 align:middle line:90%


00:35:20.430 --> 00:35:25.150 align:middle line:90%
So this is the first lemma.

00:35:25.150 --> 00:35:27.550 align:middle line:84%
And the proof idea is you
just start on either side

00:35:27.550 --> 00:35:30.270 align:middle line:84%
and write down the definition
and unwind everything.

00:35:30.270 --> 00:35:34.390 align:middle line:84%
And you use the fact
that that reduction mod

00:35:34.390 --> 00:35:37.020 align:middle line:84%
q is a ring homomorphism
and it all fits together.

00:35:37.020 --> 00:35:41.910 align:middle line:90%


00:35:41.910 --> 00:35:45.510 align:middle line:84%
So I think that my
saying that is clearer

00:35:45.510 --> 00:35:47.330 align:middle line:90%
than if I were to write it out.

00:35:47.330 --> 00:35:47.830 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:35:47.830 --> 00:35:52.870 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Do you not get the
issues from double counting them

00:35:52.870 --> 00:35:55.270 align:middle line:84%
at the left side
because you have

00:35:55.270 --> 00:35:58.140 align:middle line:90%
to make the kernel over them?

00:35:58.140 --> 00:35:58.890 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK.

00:35:58.890 --> 00:36:02.310 align:middle line:84%
So this is a homomorphism
but with a kernel.

00:36:02.310 --> 00:36:06.070 align:middle line:84%
Let's write it out and make
sure that this actually is OK.

00:36:06.070 --> 00:36:08.260 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to put the
proofs on this board

00:36:08.260 --> 00:36:11.100 align:middle line:84%
so that eventually we'll
just have this list of lemmas

00:36:11.100 --> 00:36:12.200 align:middle line:90%
that will be handy.

00:36:12.200 --> 00:36:28.160 align:middle line:90%


00:36:28.160 --> 00:36:30.400 align:middle line:84%
So here's how I like to
think about the proof.

00:36:30.400 --> 00:36:36.860 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to think of f as a
sum over n1 of a delta function

00:36:36.860 --> 00:36:38.830 align:middle line:90%
at n1 weighted by f of n1.

00:36:38.830 --> 00:36:41.700 align:middle line:90%


00:36:41.700 --> 00:36:44.340 align:middle line:90%
And I can do the same with g.

00:36:44.340 --> 00:36:49.900 align:middle line:84%
Sum over n2 delta
function of n2, g of n2.

00:36:49.900 --> 00:36:51.960 align:middle line:84%
What happens when I
take their convolution?

00:36:51.960 --> 00:36:54.580 align:middle line:90%


00:36:54.580 --> 00:36:59.020 align:middle line:84%
The multiplicative convolution
is the sum over n1 and n2.

00:36:59.020 --> 00:37:04.610 align:middle line:84%
I have a delta function at n1,
n2 weighted by f of n1, g of n2.

00:37:04.610 --> 00:37:09.300 align:middle line:90%


00:37:09.300 --> 00:37:12.080 align:middle line:84%
Let's check that this is the
same definition as before.

00:37:12.080 --> 00:37:17.120 align:middle line:84%
So if I want to evaluate
this at a point n, well,

00:37:17.120 --> 00:37:20.440 align:middle line:84%
when I evaluate
this at n it only

00:37:20.440 --> 00:37:23.000 align:middle line:90%
appears if n1 times n2 is n.

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:27.560 align:middle line:84%
So I'm summing over pairs n1
times n2 that multiply to n.

00:37:27.560 --> 00:37:29.980 align:middle line:84%
And I'm summing up
f of n1, g of n2.

00:37:29.980 --> 00:37:37.520 align:middle line:90%


00:37:37.520 --> 00:37:40.400 align:middle line:90%
Does this look OK to people?

00:37:40.400 --> 00:37:45.560 align:middle line:84%
Maybe let me add, when
I write delta n1, that's

00:37:45.560 --> 00:37:46.960 align:middle line:90%
a function of n.

00:37:46.960 --> 00:37:50.800 align:middle line:84%
And it means it's 1
if n is equal to n1,

00:37:50.800 --> 00:37:53.160 align:middle line:90%
and it's 0 otherwise.

00:37:53.160 --> 00:37:56.600 align:middle line:84%
So this delta is
a delta function.

00:37:56.600 --> 00:37:59.740 align:middle line:84%
So f is this, and g is
this, and f star g is this.

00:37:59.740 --> 00:38:07.130 align:middle line:90%


00:38:07.130 --> 00:38:11.910 align:middle line:90%
So now, what is pi qf of a?

00:38:11.910 --> 00:38:17.950 align:middle line:84%
It's the sum over n1 of a
delta function at n1 mod

00:38:17.950 --> 00:38:21.540 align:middle line:90%
q of a, f of n1.

00:38:21.540 --> 00:38:32.950 align:middle line:90%


00:38:32.950 --> 00:38:35.970 align:middle line:84%
So I like the image of f and
g as some kind of density.

00:38:35.970 --> 00:38:38.910 align:middle line:84%
So we think of f as a
description of some stuff.

00:38:38.910 --> 00:38:44.738 align:middle line:84%
And there's f of n1 stuff
located at n1, and same for g.

00:38:44.738 --> 00:38:46.030 align:middle line:90%
So what does the projection do?

00:38:46.030 --> 00:38:50.750 align:middle line:84%
It just takes the stuff at n1
and it moves it to n1 modulo q.

00:38:50.750 --> 00:38:53.550 align:middle line:84%
And stuff is coming to n1 modulo
q from several different places

00:38:53.550 --> 00:38:56.350 align:middle line:90%
and it just adds up.

00:38:56.350 --> 00:38:58.210 align:middle line:90%
And what does convolution do?

00:38:58.210 --> 00:39:03.050 align:middle line:84%
It takes every bit of stuff here
and every bit of stuff here.

00:39:03.050 --> 00:39:06.530 align:middle line:84%
It takes a bit that's at n1
here and a bit that's n2 there.

00:39:06.530 --> 00:39:10.570 align:middle line:84%
Takes those two bits and it
makes a new bit at n1 times n2.

00:39:10.570 --> 00:39:13.530 align:middle line:84%
And the weight of the
new bit is the product.

00:39:13.530 --> 00:39:16.450 align:middle line:84%
And there may be several new
bits arriving at the same place,

00:39:16.450 --> 00:39:19.410 align:middle line:90%
then we add them up.

00:39:19.410 --> 00:39:22.770 align:middle line:84%
So that's what the
projection does.

00:39:22.770 --> 00:39:27.850 align:middle line:84%
So now, if I take the
projection of f convolved

00:39:27.850 --> 00:39:34.530 align:middle line:84%
with the projection of g at a,
it's the sum over n1 and n2,

00:39:34.530 --> 00:39:46.000 align:middle line:84%
the delta function n1 times n2
mod q of a, f of n, 1, g of n2.

00:39:46.000 --> 00:40:02.680 align:middle line:90%


00:40:02.680 --> 00:40:06.620 align:middle line:84%
So then that's the same as
pi q of f convolved with g.

00:40:06.620 --> 00:40:19.880 align:middle line:90%


00:40:19.880 --> 00:40:23.440 align:middle line:84%
So all it boils down
to is, I have this bit

00:40:23.440 --> 00:40:24.920 align:middle line:90%
of f and this bit of g.

00:40:24.920 --> 00:40:27.760 align:middle line:84%
And I could first
reduce them each mod q

00:40:27.760 --> 00:40:31.760 align:middle line:84%
and then multiply them together,
or I could first multiply them

00:40:31.760 --> 00:40:34.160 align:middle line:90%
together and then reduce mod q.

00:40:34.160 --> 00:40:35.800 align:middle line:84%
And those are the
same as each other

00:40:35.800 --> 00:40:40.240 align:middle line:84%
because reduction mod
q is a homomorphism.

00:40:40.240 --> 00:40:41.650 align:middle line:90%
So that's the first lemma.

00:40:41.650 --> 00:40:50.480 align:middle line:90%


00:40:50.480 --> 00:40:55.800 align:middle line:84%
Second lemma says,
so eventually, we

00:40:55.800 --> 00:40:59.350 align:middle line:84%
would like some
L-infinity bounds.

00:40:59.350 --> 00:41:03.590 align:middle line:84%
But so far in projection theory,
we've mostly seen L2 bounds.

00:41:03.590 --> 00:41:05.870 align:middle line:84%
And they're related to
each other by basically

00:41:05.870 --> 00:41:07.750 align:middle line:90%
Cauchy-Schwarz.

00:41:07.750 --> 00:41:12.965 align:middle line:84%
So it says that if
I have f and g on Z,

00:41:12.965 --> 00:41:18.330 align:middle line:84%
q, then a multiplicative
convolution of them,

00:41:18.330 --> 00:41:23.510 align:middle line:84%
if I take the L-infinity
norm on Zq star,

00:41:23.510 --> 00:41:28.260 align:middle line:90%
that is bounded by f L2, g L2.

00:41:28.260 --> 00:41:31.750 align:middle line:90%


00:41:31.750 --> 00:41:37.150 align:middle line:84%
So in lemma 2, I think it's
important to put this star here,

00:41:37.150 --> 00:41:38.410 align:middle line:90%
multiplication.

00:41:38.410 --> 00:41:41.470 align:middle line:90%


00:41:41.470 --> 00:41:44.630 align:middle line:84%
So we leave out 0 and we leave
out things with a common factor

00:41:44.630 --> 00:41:45.310 align:middle line:90%
with q.

00:41:45.310 --> 00:41:46.750 align:middle line:84%
If you included
0, there are a lot

00:41:46.750 --> 00:41:48.690 align:middle line:84%
of ways to have a
product that makes 0,

00:41:48.690 --> 00:41:51.750 align:middle line:84%
and I felt a little worried
about how that would go.

00:41:51.750 --> 00:41:54.030 align:middle line:84%
So that's why we
have this star here.

00:41:54.030 --> 00:41:56.990 align:middle line:90%
Let's prove lemma 2.

00:41:56.990 --> 00:41:58.290 align:middle line:90%
Proof of lemma 2.

00:41:58.290 --> 00:42:01.450 align:middle line:90%


00:42:01.450 --> 00:42:09.610 align:middle line:84%
So if a is in Zq star,
then f convolved g of a

00:42:09.610 --> 00:42:17.720 align:middle line:84%
is going to be the sum b in Zq
star, f of b, g of ab inverse.

00:42:17.720 --> 00:42:21.010 align:middle line:90%


00:42:21.010 --> 00:42:21.650 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:42:21.650 --> 00:42:25.890 align:middle line:84%
Well, we're adding up over
pairs that multiply to a.

00:42:25.890 --> 00:42:30.070 align:middle line:84%
And since a is in Zq
star, a is invertible.

00:42:30.070 --> 00:42:31.790 align:middle line:84%
Each of these has
to be invertible.

00:42:31.790 --> 00:42:36.370 align:middle line:84%
So b had better also be in
Zq star, and so we get this.

00:42:36.370 --> 00:42:42.236 align:middle line:84%
And then, we use Cauchy-Schwarz,
and we bound that by f L2, g L2.

00:42:42.236 --> 00:42:56.330 align:middle line:90%


00:42:56.330 --> 00:43:03.080 align:middle line:84%
There is a small technical
issue about Zq or Zq star.

00:43:03.080 --> 00:43:04.600 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to
break something up

00:43:04.600 --> 00:43:07.760 align:middle line:84%
into a constant part and the
other part, constant part

00:43:07.760 --> 00:43:09.140 align:middle line:90%
and the high frequency part.

00:43:09.140 --> 00:43:10.765 align:middle line:84%
And it's slightly
different whether you

00:43:10.765 --> 00:43:12.760 align:middle line:90%
do this on Zq or Zq star.

00:43:12.760 --> 00:43:14.960 align:middle line:84%
It's just a minor
technical nuisance.

00:43:14.960 --> 00:43:16.820 align:middle line:84%
q is even usually
going to be prime,

00:43:16.820 --> 00:43:18.503 align:middle line:84%
so I'm just going
to be leaving out 0.

00:43:18.503 --> 00:43:19.920 align:middle line:84%
But let me just
write a lemma that

00:43:19.920 --> 00:43:21.700 align:middle line:84%
says that this isn't
such a big deal.

00:43:21.700 --> 00:43:24.600 align:middle line:90%


00:43:24.600 --> 00:43:25.540 align:middle line:90%
So a little notation.

00:43:25.540 --> 00:43:28.760 align:middle line:84%
So suppose I have
a function f on Zq.

00:43:28.760 --> 00:43:32.200 align:middle line:84%
I might be interested
in f just on Zq star.

00:43:32.200 --> 00:43:34.110 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to
call that f star.

00:43:34.110 --> 00:43:37.280 align:middle line:90%


00:43:37.280 --> 00:43:46.120 align:middle line:84%
It's just the restriction
of f to Zq star.

00:43:46.120 --> 00:43:48.160 align:middle line:84%
Now I could split
either one of these

00:43:48.160 --> 00:43:51.840 align:middle line:84%
up into a constant
part plus a leftover,

00:43:51.840 --> 00:43:54.480 align:middle line:84%
but the constants would
be slightly different.

00:43:54.480 --> 00:44:03.100 align:middle line:84%
So f is f0 plus f high,
and f star is f0 star

00:44:03.100 --> 00:44:05.860 align:middle line:90%
plus f high star.

00:44:05.860 --> 00:44:09.820 align:middle line:90%
So f0 and f0 star are constant.

00:44:09.820 --> 00:44:11.920 align:middle line:84%
And the other
pieces have mean 0,

00:44:11.920 --> 00:44:14.020 align:middle line:90%
but in slightly different sense.

00:44:14.020 --> 00:44:20.100 align:middle line:84%
So if I add up fh of a
over Z mod q, I'd get 0.

00:44:20.100 --> 00:44:28.450 align:middle line:84%
But if I add up f star
h over Zq star, I get--

00:44:28.450 --> 00:44:31.700 align:middle line:90%


00:44:31.700 --> 00:44:33.300 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:44:33.300 --> 00:44:36.200 align:middle line:84%
So I felt like I had to say
this to be honest at some point,

00:44:36.200 --> 00:44:38.060 align:middle line:90%
but it's not really a big deal.

00:44:38.060 --> 00:44:48.900 align:middle line:84%
And lemma 3 says that the L2
norm of the high star part

00:44:48.900 --> 00:44:52.580 align:middle line:84%
is at most the L2 norm
of the regular high part.

00:44:52.580 --> 00:44:56.140 align:middle line:84%
So this one lives on Zq star,
and this one lives on Zq.

00:44:56.140 --> 00:45:11.530 align:middle line:90%


00:45:11.530 --> 00:45:21.130 align:middle line:84%
And then, the last lemma says
that the high part commutes well

00:45:21.130 --> 00:45:23.810 align:middle line:90%
with multiplicative convolution.

00:45:23.810 --> 00:45:35.850 align:middle line:84%
So if f star and g star
are on Zq star, then--

00:45:35.850 --> 00:45:39.330 align:middle line:84%
there's going to be a lot
of stars in this formula--

00:45:39.330 --> 00:45:44.130 align:middle line:84%
the high part of the
convolution is the convolution

00:45:44.130 --> 00:45:44.960 align:middle line:90%
of the high parts.

00:45:44.960 --> 00:45:51.450 align:middle line:90%


00:45:51.450 --> 00:45:53.690 align:middle line:84%
We could prove all these
things if we feel like it.

00:45:53.690 --> 00:45:56.550 align:middle line:84%
They're not difficult.
I think I want

00:45:56.550 --> 00:45:58.870 align:middle line:84%
to leave it for
now, because I've

00:45:58.870 --> 00:46:02.070 align:middle line:84%
put an excessive number
of details on the board,

00:46:02.070 --> 00:46:04.870 align:middle line:84%
and try to step back, and
have a bigger picture,

00:46:04.870 --> 00:46:06.990 align:middle line:90%
and then pause and check in.

00:46:06.990 --> 00:46:11.170 align:middle line:84%
So all of these lemmas imply
the following proposition.

00:46:11.170 --> 00:46:27.910 align:middle line:90%


00:46:27.910 --> 00:46:31.630 align:middle line:84%
So maybe I have
some convolution,

00:46:31.630 --> 00:46:34.990 align:middle line:84%
some multiplicative
convolution, f star g.

00:46:34.990 --> 00:46:39.430 align:middle line:84%
And I would like to reduce
it mod q for different q's.

00:46:39.430 --> 00:46:43.430 align:middle line:90%
So I look at it projected mod q.

00:46:43.430 --> 00:46:50.390 align:middle line:84%
And then, I'm only going to be
interested in the star part.

00:46:50.390 --> 00:46:53.220 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to restrict
it to Zq star.

00:46:53.220 --> 00:46:55.680 align:middle line:84%
And I want to know whether
that's almost constant,

00:46:55.680 --> 00:46:58.020 align:middle line:84%
so I'll look at the
high part of that.

00:46:58.020 --> 00:47:01.220 align:middle line:84%
And I want to know that
that's small everywhere.

00:47:01.220 --> 00:47:04.300 align:middle line:84%
This is the kind of estimate
that we are asking about

00:47:04.300 --> 00:47:06.900 align:middle line:84%
in the Bombieri-Vinogradov
theorem

00:47:06.900 --> 00:47:12.300 align:middle line:84%
because our set of primes
is morally a multiplicative

00:47:12.300 --> 00:47:13.660 align:middle line:90%
convolution.

00:47:13.660 --> 00:47:16.580 align:middle line:84%
And I'm taking the set of
primes and reducing it mod q,

00:47:16.580 --> 00:47:20.042 align:middle line:84%
and looking at the different
classes that I have in Zq star.

00:47:20.042 --> 00:47:21.500 align:middle line:84%
And I think that
that's going to be

00:47:21.500 --> 00:47:24.860 align:middle line:84%
almost constant, so I'm going to
subtract off the constant part.

00:47:24.860 --> 00:47:26.700 align:middle line:84%
And now I want to
know that what's left

00:47:26.700 --> 00:47:30.700 align:middle line:84%
is very small everywhere, so
that's an L infinity norm.

00:47:30.700 --> 00:47:32.140 align:middle line:84%
So the Bombieri-Vinogradov
theorem

00:47:32.140 --> 00:47:34.660 align:middle line:84%
is about estimating
this kind of thing.

00:47:34.660 --> 00:47:38.100 align:middle line:84%
And the proposition says
that that is smaller

00:47:38.100 --> 00:47:52.500 align:middle line:84%
than pi q of f high L2,
pi q of g high and L2.

00:47:52.500 --> 00:47:58.440 align:middle line:90%


00:47:58.440 --> 00:48:03.600 align:middle line:84%
And it's just assembling
a bunch of those lemmas.

00:48:03.600 --> 00:48:12.520 align:middle line:84%
So the projection of the
convolution high part is the--

00:48:12.520 --> 00:48:19.832 align:middle line:90%
so proof of proposition.

00:48:19.832 --> 00:48:26.960 align:middle line:84%
We have the projection
of the convolution.

00:48:26.960 --> 00:48:27.620 align:middle line:90%
Restrict it.

00:48:27.620 --> 00:48:29.040 align:middle line:90%
Take the high part.

00:48:29.040 --> 00:48:34.480 align:middle line:84%
This is the
projection, star high

00:48:34.480 --> 00:48:40.120 align:middle line:84%
convolved with the
projection of g star high.

00:48:40.120 --> 00:48:46.200 align:middle line:90%
So that's lemma 4, high parts.

00:48:46.200 --> 00:48:47.940 align:middle line:90%
No, sorry.

00:48:47.940 --> 00:48:54.630 align:middle line:84%
This is pi q of f convolved
with pi q of g, restricted

00:48:54.630 --> 00:48:56.550 align:middle line:90%
to star high.

00:48:56.550 --> 00:48:59.430 align:middle line:90%
So that's lemma 1.

00:48:59.430 --> 00:49:02.550 align:middle line:84%
Convolution plays
well with projections.

00:49:02.550 --> 00:49:09.190 align:middle line:84%
And then, lemma 4
says that that's that.

00:49:09.190 --> 00:49:12.910 align:middle line:84%
And so now the
L-infinity norm is

00:49:12.910 --> 00:49:24.150 align:middle line:84%
bounded by pi q of f star high
L2, pi q of g star high L2.

00:49:24.150 --> 00:49:25.330 align:middle line:90%
That's lemma 3.

00:49:25.330 --> 00:49:31.670 align:middle line:90%


00:49:31.670 --> 00:49:34.230 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, that's lemma 2.

00:49:34.230 --> 00:49:44.990 align:middle line:84%
And then, that's bounded by just
pi q of f high L2, pi q of g L2,

00:49:44.990 --> 00:49:46.030 align:middle line:90%
and that's lemma.

00:49:46.030 --> 00:50:06.890 align:middle line:90%


00:50:06.890 --> 00:50:12.330 align:middle line:84%
So let me summarize a little
bit and then pause to check in.

00:50:12.330 --> 00:50:15.890 align:middle line:84%
So an issue that
we're dealing with

00:50:15.890 --> 00:50:18.145 align:middle line:84%
is L2 norms versus
L-infinity norms.

00:50:18.145 --> 00:50:19.770 align:middle line:84%
Because we're trying
to prove something

00:50:19.770 --> 00:50:22.270 align:middle line:84%
that's true for
every moduli class,

00:50:22.270 --> 00:50:23.810 align:middle line:90%
so it's an L-infinity norm.

00:50:23.810 --> 00:50:26.370 align:middle line:84%
But our techniques that
come from Fourier analysis,

00:50:26.370 --> 00:50:29.250 align:middle line:84%
and so on, it usually
tells us about L2 norms.

00:50:29.250 --> 00:50:31.290 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a
bound like this,

00:50:31.290 --> 00:50:35.570 align:middle line:84%
it tells you that pi q of f
is pretty evenly distributed,

00:50:35.570 --> 00:50:38.275 align:middle line:90%
at most a.

00:50:38.275 --> 00:50:39.650 align:middle line:84%
And we're trying
to prove a bound

00:50:39.650 --> 00:50:41.930 align:middle line:84%
like this that says that
the projection of this thing

00:50:41.930 --> 00:50:46.560 align:middle line:84%
is pretty evenly
distributed at every a.

00:50:46.560 --> 00:50:48.300 align:middle line:84%
And the point of
this proposition,

00:50:48.300 --> 00:50:52.160 align:middle line:84%
it says that if pi
q of f and pi q of g

00:50:52.160 --> 00:50:55.960 align:middle line:84%
are pretty evenly
distributed, just at most a,

00:50:55.960 --> 00:50:58.640 align:middle line:84%
then the projection
of their convolution

00:50:58.640 --> 00:51:03.160 align:middle line:84%
is pretty evenly
distributed at every a.

00:51:03.160 --> 00:51:06.510 align:middle line:84%
And so that's why being
a convolution is helpful.

00:51:06.510 --> 00:51:21.160 align:middle line:90%


00:51:21.160 --> 00:51:23.090 align:middle line:84%
So a little pause for
questions and comments.

00:51:23.090 --> 00:51:31.400 align:middle line:90%


00:51:31.400 --> 00:51:33.260 align:middle line:90%
OK, cool.

00:51:33.260 --> 00:51:34.920 align:middle line:90%
So now let's go on.

00:51:34.920 --> 00:51:39.640 align:middle line:84%
And these two things are
controlled by the large sieve.

00:51:39.640 --> 00:51:42.540 align:middle line:84%
The large sieve tells us
that if f is some function,

00:51:42.540 --> 00:51:46.340 align:middle line:84%
then this L2 norm
is small for most q.

00:51:46.340 --> 00:51:48.540 align:middle line:84%
And so we're going to
write down that bound

00:51:48.540 --> 00:51:49.900 align:middle line:90%
and see how small it is.

00:51:49.900 --> 00:51:52.400 align:middle line:84%
And then, we're going to plug
it into this proposition.

00:51:52.400 --> 00:51:53.680 align:middle line:90%
We'll get a bound for this.

00:51:53.680 --> 00:52:13.360 align:middle line:90%


00:52:13.360 --> 00:52:14.490 align:middle line:90%
So large sieve.

00:52:14.490 --> 00:52:17.020 align:middle line:90%


00:52:17.020 --> 00:52:25.260 align:middle line:84%
So remember that Pm is the
set of p prime, p around m.

00:52:25.260 --> 00:52:29.460 align:middle line:84%
And so we proved in
class, and so we'll always

00:52:29.460 --> 00:52:32.680 align:middle line:84%
have a function which is
defined on the integers up to N,

00:52:32.680 --> 00:52:36.700 align:middle line:84%
and it goes to C. And we
proved in class that if you

00:52:36.700 --> 00:52:41.780 align:middle line:90%
take the sum p and Pm of--

00:52:41.780 --> 00:52:43.210 align:middle line:84%
so in class, we
thought about what

00:52:43.210 --> 00:52:46.370 align:middle line:84%
happens if M is smaller than
the square root of N. Then,

00:52:46.370 --> 00:52:52.930 align:middle line:84%
we got the sum pi q
of f high L2 squared.

00:52:52.930 --> 00:52:58.540 align:middle line:84%
And that is bounded by N/M
times just f L2 squared.

00:52:58.540 --> 00:53:06.010 align:middle line:90%


00:53:06.010 --> 00:53:08.690 align:middle line:84%
M could be bigger than N to
1/2, and that will be relevant,

00:53:08.690 --> 00:53:10.630 align:middle line:84%
and this story is
often relevant.

00:53:10.630 --> 00:53:12.890 align:middle line:84%
And the proof idea is
the same, but then it

00:53:12.890 --> 00:53:14.730 align:middle line:84%
works out a little
bit differently.

00:53:14.730 --> 00:53:20.290 align:middle line:84%
So if M is bigger than N to 1/2,
then this same sum is bounded

00:53:20.290 --> 00:53:24.170 align:middle line:90%
by M times f L2 squared.

00:53:24.170 --> 00:53:30.010 align:middle line:84%
So this one was in class, and
this one is on the homework.

00:53:30.010 --> 00:53:33.030 align:middle line:84%
So I posted the
homework for next week,

00:53:33.030 --> 00:53:34.945 align:middle line:84%
and the first
problem is to do this

00:53:34.945 --> 00:53:36.570 align:middle line:84%
mostly as a way of
thinking through how

00:53:36.570 --> 00:53:38.330 align:middle line:90%
the large sieve worked.

00:53:38.330 --> 00:53:40.610 align:middle line:84%
And then the second bit
is about Linnik's thing

00:53:40.610 --> 00:53:41.730 align:middle line:90%
about quadratic residues.

00:53:41.730 --> 00:53:51.080 align:middle line:90%


00:53:51.080 --> 00:53:58.130 align:middle line:84%
So now we are going to plug
these things into here.

00:53:58.130 --> 00:54:00.720 align:middle line:90%


00:54:00.720 --> 00:54:03.750 align:middle line:84%
So we get, all together,
I'll call it a theorem.

00:54:03.750 --> 00:54:06.800 align:middle line:90%


00:54:06.800 --> 00:54:09.320 align:middle line:90%
Let's say like this.

00:54:09.320 --> 00:54:13.920 align:middle line:84%
So suppose f is a
function on N1 up to C,

00:54:13.920 --> 00:54:19.120 align:middle line:84%
and g is a function
on numbers up to N2.

00:54:19.120 --> 00:54:22.340 align:middle line:84%
And so if I take their
multiplicative convolution,

00:54:22.340 --> 00:54:25.200 align:middle line:84%
that will be a function
on the integers up to N,

00:54:25.200 --> 00:54:26.890 align:middle line:90%
where N is N1 times N2.

00:54:26.890 --> 00:54:31.680 align:middle line:90%


00:54:31.680 --> 00:54:45.780 align:middle line:84%
And then, I can take the sum p
and Pm of f convolved with g.

00:54:45.780 --> 00:54:49.020 align:middle line:90%
I project it mod q.

00:54:49.020 --> 00:54:51.435 align:middle line:84%
I maybe take the high,
take the star part.

00:54:51.435 --> 00:54:54.060 align:middle line:84%
That doesn't matter if you do it
or not, but in our application

00:54:54.060 --> 00:54:57.798 align:middle line:84%
we'll do it, and then
subtract off the constant.

00:54:57.798 --> 00:54:59.340 align:middle line:84%
So the idea is that
this thing should

00:54:59.340 --> 00:55:01.720 align:middle line:84%
be pretty close to
constant much of the time.

00:55:01.720 --> 00:55:03.440 align:middle line:84%
So we look at the
non-constant part.

00:55:03.440 --> 00:55:06.380 align:middle line:90%


00:55:06.380 --> 00:55:09.180 align:middle line:84%
And then, that is
bounded by, there's

00:55:09.180 --> 00:55:11.100 align:middle line:84%
an expression that's
slightly messy.

00:55:11.100 --> 00:55:17.860 align:middle line:90%
And then, we have f L2 and g L2.

00:55:17.860 --> 00:55:23.260 align:middle line:84%
And the thing that goes in
here when you work it out is--

00:55:23.260 --> 00:55:24.080 align:middle line:90%
I'll have to check.

00:55:24.080 --> 00:55:50.810 align:middle line:90%


00:55:50.810 --> 00:55:51.330 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:55:51.330 --> 00:55:54.250 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: When you're
defining the convolution of f

00:55:54.250 --> 00:55:58.290 align:middle line:84%
and g is a function that
can be integers up to N,

00:55:58.290 --> 00:56:02.650 align:middle line:84%
how is that defined for
the product pair 1 times

00:56:02.650 --> 00:56:05.230 align:middle line:90%
N for N large?

00:56:05.230 --> 00:56:08.942 align:middle line:84%
Because f and g are individually
only defined up to N1 and N2,

00:56:08.942 --> 00:56:10.770 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:56:10.770 --> 00:56:11.728 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yes.

00:56:11.728 --> 00:56:12.270 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:56:12.270 --> 00:56:15.870 align:middle line:84%
So you should imagine f and g
being extended as 0 beyond that.

00:56:15.870 --> 00:56:20.830 align:middle line:90%


00:56:20.830 --> 00:56:23.130 align:middle line:84%
So the question
was how to define

00:56:23.130 --> 00:56:24.670 align:middle line:90%
in the definition of this.

00:56:24.670 --> 00:56:27.890 align:middle line:84%
We'll have all the pairs,
little n1 times little n2,

00:56:27.890 --> 00:56:29.330 align:middle line:90%
that multiply to n.

00:56:29.330 --> 00:56:32.090 align:middle line:84%
And it could happen that
little n1 or little n2 are

00:56:32.090 --> 00:56:34.710 align:middle line:90%
too big to lie in this region.

00:56:34.710 --> 00:56:37.130 align:middle line:90%
And then we just set f to be 0.

00:56:37.130 --> 00:56:44.467 align:middle line:90%


00:56:44.467 --> 00:56:45.050 align:middle line:90%
Oh, and sorry.

00:56:45.050 --> 00:56:46.290 align:middle line:90%
And this is L infinity.

00:56:46.290 --> 00:56:47.100 align:middle line:90%
It's not L2.

00:56:47.100 --> 00:56:57.985 align:middle line:90%


00:56:57.985 --> 00:57:03.628 align:middle line:84%
So one thing that
I find a little

00:57:03.628 --> 00:57:05.670 align:middle line:84%
difficult about the proof,
or teaching the proof,

00:57:05.670 --> 00:57:10.230 align:middle line:84%
is that the formulas are
a little bit complicated.

00:57:10.230 --> 00:57:14.230 align:middle line:84%
But the idea of this is to
just combine the large sieve

00:57:14.230 --> 00:57:15.790 align:middle line:90%
and this proposition.

00:57:15.790 --> 00:57:20.790 align:middle line:84%
So if you start with the
left-hand side and you just

00:57:20.790 --> 00:57:29.870 align:middle line:84%
apply this proposition,
then we get--

00:57:29.870 --> 00:57:32.870 align:middle line:84%
yeah, I guess we
don't need that.

00:57:32.870 --> 00:57:44.620 align:middle line:84%
We get a sum, p and Pm of pi
q of f high L2, pi q of g high

00:57:44.620 --> 00:57:45.130 align:middle line:90%
and L2.

00:57:45.130 --> 00:57:47.940 align:middle line:90%


00:57:47.940 --> 00:57:50.220 align:middle line:84%
So the proposition just said
that this L-infinity norm

00:57:50.220 --> 00:57:51.940 align:middle line:90%
is bounded by this product.

00:57:51.940 --> 00:57:55.100 align:middle line:90%
I copied down the sum.

00:57:55.100 --> 00:57:58.860 align:middle line:84%
And then this looks a lot like
the input of the large sieve.

00:57:58.860 --> 00:58:06.340 align:middle line:84%
So if I Cauchy-Schwarz it, I
get the sum pi q of f high L2

00:58:06.340 --> 00:58:19.300 align:middle line:84%
squared to the 1/2, and then the
sum pi q of g high L2 squared

00:58:19.300 --> 00:58:19.900 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2.

00:58:19.900 --> 00:58:22.460 align:middle line:90%


00:58:22.460 --> 00:58:24.320 align:middle line:84%
And then I apply
the large sieve.

00:58:24.320 --> 00:58:27.220 align:middle line:90%


00:58:27.220 --> 00:58:30.380 align:middle line:84%
So the large sieve gives a
bound for each of these things

00:58:30.380 --> 00:58:31.640 align:middle line:90%
and I plug it in.

00:58:31.640 --> 00:58:33.140 align:middle line:84%
And what makes it
a little bit messy

00:58:33.140 --> 00:58:36.000 align:middle line:84%
is that, because there are
two cases, the bound for this

00:58:36.000 --> 00:58:39.760 align:middle line:84%
is a sum of two terms,
and the bound for this

00:58:39.760 --> 00:58:42.320 align:middle line:90%
is a sum of two terms.

00:58:42.320 --> 00:58:44.140 align:middle line:84%
So then, when I
multiply that together,

00:58:44.140 --> 00:58:47.100 align:middle line:84%
I get this sum of two terms
times that sum of two terms.

00:58:47.100 --> 00:59:06.120 align:middle line:90%


00:59:06.120 --> 00:59:16.960 align:middle line:84%
In the setting of our
main theorem about primes,

00:59:16.960 --> 00:59:19.480 align:middle line:84%
the theorem of
Rényi, and Bombieri,

00:59:19.480 --> 00:59:27.000 align:middle line:84%
and Vinogradov, the size
of f and the size of g

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:30.680 align:middle line:84%
would be around 1
where they're defined.

00:59:30.680 --> 00:59:39.110 align:middle line:84%
And so the L2 norms of f and
g would be around N1 and N2,

00:59:39.110 --> 00:59:43.990 align:middle line:90%
and squared would be around N2.

00:59:43.990 --> 00:59:47.270 align:middle line:84%
So if you plug that
all in, then we'd

00:59:47.270 --> 01:00:05.630 align:middle line:84%
get our sum L infinity
would be bounded by N/m,

01:00:05.630 --> 01:00:11.590 align:middle line:84%
plus the square root of N1, N,
plus the square root of N2, N,

01:00:11.590 --> 01:00:26.035 align:middle line:90%
plus M root N.

01:00:26.035 --> 01:00:32.570 align:middle line:84%
And then, our goal would be that
this sum is much smaller than N.

01:00:32.570 --> 01:00:39.890 align:middle line:84%
So it's good as long as M
is less than N to 1/2 minus

01:00:39.890 --> 01:00:40.670 align:middle line:90%
epsilon.

01:00:40.670 --> 01:00:44.530 align:middle line:84%
That's where that condition
comes from, the range of q,

01:00:44.530 --> 01:00:57.850 align:middle line:84%
and as long as N1 and N2
are much smaller than N.

01:00:57.850 --> 01:01:04.063 align:middle line:84%
So in this part, I redid
the computation at home

01:01:04.063 --> 01:01:05.230 align:middle line:90%
and it's a little bit messy.

01:01:05.230 --> 01:01:08.650 align:middle line:84%
I did spend some
time trying to think

01:01:08.650 --> 01:01:10.970 align:middle line:84%
if there's a way of saying
it without computing

01:01:10.970 --> 01:01:15.370 align:middle line:84%
to see when it works well and
when it doesn't work well.

01:01:15.370 --> 01:01:17.930 align:middle line:84%
I have a couple
comments about that,

01:01:17.930 --> 01:01:19.570 align:middle line:84%
although I don't
feel like I know how

01:01:19.570 --> 01:01:23.050 align:middle line:90%
to see everything that way yet.

01:01:23.050 --> 01:01:26.530 align:middle line:84%
So one comment is
that it doesn't

01:01:26.530 --> 01:01:30.400 align:middle line:84%
work very well if N1
or N2 is almost N.

01:01:30.400 --> 01:01:34.480 align:middle line:84%
And there's a conceptual
reason for that.

01:01:34.480 --> 01:01:41.040 align:middle line:84%
So suppose N2 was N.
That means N1 would be 1.

01:01:41.040 --> 01:01:44.160 align:middle line:84%
So my f is supported
just on 1, and my g

01:01:44.160 --> 01:01:46.760 align:middle line:84%
is supported all
the way up to N.

01:01:46.760 --> 01:01:49.880 align:middle line:84%
And when I convolve
them together,

01:01:49.880 --> 01:01:55.200 align:middle line:84%
I just get g times
the value of f at 1.

01:01:55.200 --> 01:01:59.360 align:middle line:84%
So in that situation
there's no special structure

01:01:59.360 --> 01:02:00.640 align:middle line:90%
of this function.

01:02:00.640 --> 01:02:03.800 align:middle line:84%
It's a totally
arbitrary function.

01:02:03.800 --> 01:02:05.680 align:middle line:84%
And since this kind
of theorem is not

01:02:05.680 --> 01:02:07.680 align:middle line:84%
true for arbitrary
functions, it can't

01:02:07.680 --> 01:02:16.545 align:middle line:84%
work when N1 and N2
are really close to N.

01:02:16.545 --> 01:02:19.880 align:middle line:84%
So as long as N1 and
N2 are kind of even,

01:02:19.880 --> 01:02:23.040 align:middle line:84%
there's a meaningful
convolution going on.

01:02:23.040 --> 01:02:25.480 align:middle line:84%
As long as neither of them is
close to 1, neither of them

01:02:25.480 --> 01:02:28.500 align:middle line:84%
is close to N, there's a
meaningful convolution structure

01:02:28.500 --> 01:02:29.280 align:middle line:90%
going on.

01:02:29.280 --> 01:02:31.920 align:middle line:84%
And in that setting,
these terms are OK.

01:02:31.920 --> 01:02:34.580 align:middle line:90%


01:02:34.580 --> 01:02:40.460 align:middle line:84%
This term here is OK
as long as M is big.

01:02:40.460 --> 01:02:41.293 align:middle line:90%
M is reasonably big.

01:02:41.293 --> 01:02:43.835 align:middle line:84%
We need M to be reasonably big
so that we're actually looking

01:02:43.835 --> 01:02:45.100 align:middle line:90%
at many different projections.

01:02:45.100 --> 01:02:46.975 align:middle line:84%
Because we're just
looking at one projection,

01:02:46.975 --> 01:02:49.450 align:middle line:84%
we can never say
anything about it

01:02:49.450 --> 01:02:52.300 align:middle line:90%
by just using projection theory

01:02:52.300 --> 01:02:54.780 align:middle line:84%
And here, we need M
to be not too much

01:02:54.780 --> 01:03:02.420 align:middle line:84%
bigger than the square root of
N. And the reason for that is,

01:03:02.420 --> 01:03:05.400 align:middle line:84%
so one important case here
is when N1 and N2 are equal.

01:03:05.400 --> 01:03:08.620 align:middle line:84%
So they would both be
the square root of N.

01:03:08.620 --> 01:03:11.160 align:middle line:84%
And if M is bigger than
the square root of N,

01:03:11.160 --> 01:03:15.700 align:middle line:84%
M would be bigger
than both N1 and N2.

01:03:15.700 --> 01:03:21.020 align:middle line:84%
And when that happens, the
theorem might still be true,

01:03:21.020 --> 01:03:23.780 align:middle line:84%
but the proof doesn't
work very well.

01:03:23.780 --> 01:03:28.250 align:middle line:84%
You see, if M is
bigger than N1 and N2,

01:03:28.250 --> 01:03:31.890 align:middle line:84%
I have this function f that's
defined on the numbers up to N1.

01:03:31.890 --> 01:03:37.690 align:middle line:84%
And then, I tried projecting
it mod q, where q is around M.

01:03:37.690 --> 01:03:39.470 align:middle line:90%
So q is actually bigger than N1.

01:03:39.470 --> 01:03:44.170 align:middle line:84%
So this projection operation
is extremely uninteresting.

01:03:44.170 --> 01:03:48.040 align:middle line:84%
The first N1 elements I copied
down, and the rest I put 0.

01:03:48.040 --> 01:03:50.690 align:middle line:90%


01:03:50.690 --> 01:03:55.170 align:middle line:84%
So since that projection
operation is trivial,

01:03:55.170 --> 01:03:57.810 align:middle line:84%
no theorem from
projection theory

01:03:57.810 --> 01:03:59.870 align:middle line:84%
is going to say
anything useful here.

01:03:59.870 --> 01:04:04.770 align:middle line:90%


01:04:04.770 --> 01:04:09.890 align:middle line:84%
The gain that we're getting
is that as long as--

01:04:09.890 --> 01:04:14.970 align:middle line:84%
so I need either N1 or N2
to be bigger than M in order

01:04:14.970 --> 01:04:16.370 align:middle line:90%
to get off the ground.

01:04:16.370 --> 01:04:22.410 align:middle line:84%
Once N1 or N2 is bigger than M,
let's say N2 is bigger than M,

01:04:22.410 --> 01:04:25.390 align:middle line:84%
then, when I look at these
projections, most of them

01:04:25.390 --> 01:04:28.343 align:middle line:90%
are almost constant.

01:04:28.343 --> 01:04:30.010 align:middle line:84%
That's where the
mileage is coming from.

01:04:30.010 --> 01:04:32.070 align:middle line:84%
So these guys are
almost constant.

01:04:32.070 --> 01:04:34.290 align:middle line:84%
These guys might or might
not be almost constant.

01:04:34.290 --> 01:04:36.590 align:middle line:90%
It's OK either way.

01:04:36.590 --> 01:04:38.370 align:middle line:84%
And then, when I
convolve it together,

01:04:38.370 --> 01:04:40.450 align:middle line:84%
the convolution is
almost constant.

01:04:40.450 --> 01:04:42.570 align:middle line:84%
And in a strong
sense, it's everywhere

01:04:42.570 --> 01:04:45.680 align:middle line:84%
almost constant, instead of just
most places almost constant.

01:04:45.680 --> 01:04:54.590 align:middle line:90%


01:04:54.590 --> 01:04:56.930 align:middle line:84%
Actually, another
visual thing is,

01:04:56.930 --> 01:04:59.970 align:middle line:84%
so say this guy is almost
constant but not everywhere.

01:04:59.970 --> 01:05:02.950 align:middle line:84%
So in most places it's almost
constant, but a couple of places

01:05:02.950 --> 01:05:04.990 align:middle line:90%
it has a big bump.

01:05:04.990 --> 01:05:11.030 align:middle line:84%
When I take this convolution,
then to evaluate the convolution

01:05:11.030 --> 01:05:14.230 align:middle line:84%
at any given point, I have to
look at the contribution of this

01:05:14.230 --> 01:05:15.790 align:middle line:90%
at every point.

01:05:15.790 --> 01:05:18.810 align:middle line:84%
And so those couple of places
only contribute a little.

01:05:18.810 --> 01:05:22.267 align:middle line:84%
And mostly I see the
contribution of the places

01:05:22.267 --> 01:05:23.100 align:middle line:90%
where this is small.

01:05:23.100 --> 01:05:26.540 align:middle line:90%


01:05:26.540 --> 01:05:27.880 align:middle line:90%
So that's what's going on.

01:05:27.880 --> 01:05:30.380 align:middle line:84%
And then you do have
to do some algebra

01:05:30.380 --> 01:05:32.840 align:middle line:84%
to see just how much
we learned from that.

01:05:32.840 --> 01:05:37.060 align:middle line:90%


01:05:37.060 --> 01:05:39.430 align:middle line:84%
So now let's go
back to our theorem.

01:05:39.430 --> 01:06:00.860 align:middle line:90%


01:06:00.860 --> 01:06:03.940 align:middle line:84%
And this last part I'm not
going to do every detail, which

01:06:03.940 --> 01:06:05.560 align:middle line:90%
even gets a little bit messier.

01:06:05.560 --> 01:06:11.180 align:middle line:84%
But I'll just say the
skeleton and then we'll pause.

01:06:11.180 --> 01:06:17.020 align:middle line:84%
So let's say that S is
the primes up to N to 1/2.

01:06:17.020 --> 01:06:25.760 align:middle line:84%
And then, remember that if,
say, N over 2 is less than p,

01:06:25.760 --> 01:06:31.040 align:middle line:84%
is less than N, or actually,
just N to 1/2 is less than N,

01:06:31.040 --> 01:06:38.000 align:middle line:84%
then R relatively prime
to S of n is prime.

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:39.760 align:middle line:84%
So we can basically
study this function

01:06:39.760 --> 01:06:42.880 align:middle line:90%
by studying that function.

01:06:42.880 --> 01:06:47.520 align:middle line:84%
And then, we also know that
relatively prime S of N

01:06:47.520 --> 01:06:54.520 align:middle line:84%
is 1 convolved with
Dp1, convolved with Dpr.

01:06:54.520 --> 01:06:58.960 align:middle line:84%
And these are all
multiplicative convolutions.

01:06:58.960 --> 01:07:02.500 align:middle line:84%
This whole thing is a ton of
multiplicative convolutions.

01:07:02.500 --> 01:07:06.040 align:middle line:84%
But if I just want
to see two of them,

01:07:06.040 --> 01:07:09.780 align:middle line:84%
then I could say it's this
guy convolved with that guy.

01:07:09.780 --> 01:07:13.640 align:middle line:90%


01:07:13.640 --> 01:07:19.460 align:middle line:84%
Now this function, as
written, it goes on forever,

01:07:19.460 --> 01:07:21.430 align:middle line:84%
and this function
goes on forever.

01:07:21.430 --> 01:07:23.870 align:middle line:84%
But I only want to
evaluate this up

01:07:23.870 --> 01:07:33.910 align:middle line:84%
to capital N. So this guy
at N1 and this guy at N2,

01:07:33.910 --> 01:07:36.970 align:middle line:84%
after they come together
in the convolution,

01:07:36.970 --> 01:07:39.230 align:middle line:84%
they'll only be relevant
if N1 times N2 is less

01:07:39.230 --> 01:07:43.790 align:middle line:84%
than capital N.
So what I'll do is

01:07:43.790 --> 01:07:48.430 align:middle line:84%
I'll write this as
a sum on I1 of f

01:07:48.430 --> 01:07:50.950 align:middle line:84%
times the characteristic
function of I1.

01:07:50.950 --> 01:07:54.750 align:middle line:84%
So I'll just divide up the
numbers into some intervals.

01:07:54.750 --> 01:08:00.230 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to convolve
that with the sum over I2 of g

01:08:00.230 --> 01:08:03.590 align:middle line:90%
characteristic function of I2.

01:08:03.590 --> 01:08:05.330 align:middle line:84%
And I can open up
the parentheses.

01:08:05.330 --> 01:08:15.500 align:middle line:84%
It's the sum, I1 and I2, of f
I1, f I1 convolved with g I2.

01:08:15.500 --> 01:08:23.640 align:middle line:90%


01:08:23.640 --> 01:08:27.340 align:middle line:84%
And now if I only want to
capture this up to capital N,

01:08:27.340 --> 01:08:33.020 align:middle line:84%
so let me say that N1
is the maximum of I1,

01:08:33.020 --> 01:08:35.129 align:middle line:90%
and N2 is the maximum of I2.

01:08:35.129 --> 01:08:38.899 align:middle line:90%


01:08:38.899 --> 01:08:44.700 align:middle line:84%
So for little n less than or
equal to capital N, R Ps of n

01:08:44.700 --> 01:08:51.939 align:middle line:84%
will be the sum over I1, I2 of
f characteristic function of I1

01:08:51.939 --> 01:08:55.620 align:middle line:84%
convolved with g
characteristic function of I2.

01:08:55.620 --> 01:09:05.288 align:middle line:84%
And here, I can assume that N1
times N2 is less than around N.

01:09:05.288 --> 01:09:06.830 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I should make
this the minimum.

01:09:06.830 --> 01:09:11.540 align:middle line:90%


01:09:11.540 --> 01:09:14.140 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, because otherwise the
product of these two intervals

01:09:14.140 --> 01:09:16.300 align:middle line:84%
will be bigger than
capital N, so it

01:09:16.300 --> 01:09:17.939 align:middle line:90%
won't have any influence here.

01:09:17.939 --> 01:09:26.520 align:middle line:90%


01:09:26.520 --> 01:09:38.840 align:middle line:84%
So then for each of these we
apply the theorem, theorem A,

01:09:38.840 --> 01:09:40.439 align:middle line:90%
that theorem there.

01:09:40.439 --> 01:09:43.960 align:middle line:84%
And it tells me that when I
reduce these things, mod q,

01:09:43.960 --> 01:09:48.180 align:middle line:84%
for most q's, the non-constant
part is small in L infinity.

01:09:48.180 --> 01:09:51.600 align:middle line:90%


01:09:51.600 --> 01:09:54.350 align:middle line:84%
So this works for
most of the terms.

01:09:54.350 --> 01:09:57.520 align:middle line:90%


01:09:57.520 --> 01:10:03.440 align:middle line:84%
It works as long as N1 and
N2 are much bigger than 1,

01:10:03.440 --> 01:10:11.560 align:middle line:84%
and much less than N,
but it could happen.

01:10:11.560 --> 01:10:17.610 align:middle line:84%
A piece of this would be this
guy with I2 very close to 1,

01:10:17.610 --> 01:10:20.550 align:middle line:84%
or even just the 0.1,
convolved with that guy.

01:10:20.550 --> 01:10:22.510 align:middle line:90%
That's in there, too.

01:10:22.510 --> 01:10:24.590 align:middle line:90%
How do you deal with that?

01:10:24.590 --> 01:10:29.390 align:middle line:84%
Well, this function f
is itself a convolution.

01:10:29.390 --> 01:10:34.010 align:middle line:84%
So then I can take f and I
split it up, and I keep going.

01:10:34.010 --> 01:10:39.670 align:middle line:90%


01:10:39.670 --> 01:10:45.950 align:middle line:84%
So if N1 is almost N,
and N2 is almost 1,

01:10:45.950 --> 01:10:51.190 align:middle line:84%
use f is f1 convolved
with f2, dot, dot, dot.

01:10:51.190 --> 01:10:54.910 align:middle line:84%
So this part gets
a little bit messy.

01:10:54.910 --> 01:10:59.470 align:middle line:84%
And to be honest,
I'm not positive

01:10:59.470 --> 01:11:01.355 align:middle line:90%
whether this exact thing works.

01:11:01.355 --> 01:11:02.480 align:middle line:90%
This is a possible project.

01:11:02.480 --> 01:11:06.390 align:middle line:90%


01:11:06.390 --> 01:11:08.990 align:middle line:84%
So what I read in analytic
number theory books

01:11:08.990 --> 01:11:11.830 align:middle line:84%
is a slightly
fancier way of taking

01:11:11.830 --> 01:11:14.390 align:middle line:84%
this function, characteristic
function of prime numbers,

01:11:14.390 --> 01:11:19.450 align:middle line:84%
and writing it in terms of some
multiplicative convolutions.

01:11:19.450 --> 01:11:20.950 align:middle line:84%
And for the slightly
fancier way,

01:11:20.950 --> 01:11:22.670 align:middle line:84%
there end up being
less terms here,

01:11:22.670 --> 01:11:25.450 align:middle line:90%
and it works out more cleanly.

01:11:25.450 --> 01:11:28.290 align:middle line:84%
But it also, at least I had
a little bit more trouble

01:11:28.290 --> 01:11:30.550 align:middle line:84%
motivating it and seeing
how people thought of it.

01:11:30.550 --> 01:11:33.210 align:middle line:90%


01:11:33.210 --> 01:11:34.990 align:middle line:90%
Anyway, so I'm not positive.

01:11:34.990 --> 01:11:39.410 align:middle line:84%
I think that this may work in
all details, or maybe not quite.

01:11:39.410 --> 01:11:42.610 align:middle line:84%
Maybe it requires
more fidgeting.

01:11:42.610 --> 01:11:44.170 align:middle line:84%
But nevertheless,
I think it shows

01:11:44.170 --> 01:11:46.290 align:middle line:84%
the main ideas that
go into proving

01:11:46.290 --> 01:11:48.070 align:middle line:90%
the Bombieri-Vinogradov theorem.

01:11:48.070 --> 01:11:57.850 align:middle line:90%


01:11:57.850 --> 01:12:00.110 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Sorry, I'm
still really confused.

01:12:00.110 --> 01:12:04.430 align:middle line:84%
So what are those
intervals, I1 and I2?

01:12:04.430 --> 01:12:07.970 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: What are
the intervals I1 and I2?

01:12:07.970 --> 01:12:10.810 align:middle line:84%
So you might first
try dyadic intervals.

01:12:10.810 --> 01:12:17.200 align:middle line:90%


01:12:17.200 --> 01:12:22.040 align:middle line:84%
And so modulo technical
details, that's good.

01:12:22.040 --> 01:12:23.680 align:middle line:84%
But actually, there's
a little problem

01:12:23.680 --> 01:12:29.280 align:middle line:84%
with taking dyadic intervals
that wherever you stop,

01:12:29.280 --> 01:12:31.880 align:middle line:84%
this function will be exactly
the function that we want up

01:12:31.880 --> 01:12:35.840 align:middle line:84%
to capital N. And then it'll go
a little bit beyond capital N.

01:12:35.840 --> 01:12:38.560 align:middle line:84%
And there'll be
some stuff that's

01:12:38.560 --> 01:12:43.200 align:middle line:84%
not exactly this function
anymore, and then it'll die off.

01:12:43.200 --> 01:12:45.880 align:middle line:84%
And we'd like to prove that
you just take this function

01:12:45.880 --> 01:12:47.680 align:middle line:84%
and sharply cut
it off at capital

01:12:47.680 --> 01:12:50.520 align:middle line:84%
N. We'd like that to
be evenly distributed.

01:12:50.520 --> 01:12:55.440 align:middle line:84%
But we have this
extra junk at the end.

01:12:55.440 --> 01:12:56.780 align:middle line:90%
OK, so that's a problem.

01:12:56.780 --> 01:12:58.520 align:middle line:84%
And the solution
to that problem is

01:12:58.520 --> 01:13:01.320 align:middle line:84%
we can greatly reduce
the amount of junk

01:13:01.320 --> 01:13:03.560 align:middle line:84%
by replacing dyadic
intervals by intervals

01:13:03.560 --> 01:13:06.200 align:middle line:90%
that are somewhat narrower.

01:13:06.200 --> 01:13:11.000 align:middle line:84%
If we make I1 and I2 narrow,
then whenever I1 times I2

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:14.160 align:middle line:84%
crosses over N, it will only
cross over a little bit,

01:13:14.160 --> 01:13:16.820 align:middle line:84%
so we'll have only a
little bit of junk.

01:13:16.820 --> 01:13:19.758 align:middle line:90%
So that's who I1 and I2 are.

01:13:19.758 --> 01:13:20.300 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: OK.

01:13:20.300 --> 01:13:25.627 align:middle line:90%


01:13:25.627 --> 01:13:26.460 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah?

01:13:26.460 --> 01:13:31.067 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Can you recap what
properties of R Ps we used?

01:13:31.067 --> 01:13:31.900 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah.

01:13:31.900 --> 01:13:36.500 align:middle line:84%
The question was, can we recap
what properties of R Ps we used?

01:13:36.500 --> 01:13:41.060 align:middle line:84%
So the first property is
that R Ps detects primes.

01:13:41.060 --> 01:13:43.500 align:middle line:84%
And that property
is written here.

01:13:43.500 --> 01:13:46.180 align:middle line:84%
So s is the primes that
are less than N to 1/2.

01:13:46.180 --> 01:13:49.180 align:middle line:84%
And on this big
region, R Ps of n

01:13:49.180 --> 01:13:51.140 align:middle line:84%
is the same as just
characteristic function

01:13:51.140 --> 01:13:51.780 align:middle line:90%
of primes.

01:13:51.780 --> 01:13:55.440 align:middle line:90%
It tells us who's prime.

01:13:55.440 --> 01:13:59.600 align:middle line:84%
But this function is nicer than
this function on the face of it

01:13:59.600 --> 01:14:01.540 align:middle line:84%
because as a second
good property,

01:14:01.540 --> 01:14:04.390 align:middle line:84%
which is that it is a
multiplicative convolution

01:14:04.390 --> 01:14:05.890 align:middle line:84%
of a whole bunch
of things together.

01:14:05.890 --> 01:14:09.540 align:middle line:90%


01:14:09.540 --> 01:14:12.150 align:middle line:84%
And so we, in particular,
can split it up like this.

01:14:12.150 --> 01:14:14.410 align:middle line:84%
And we see it has this
multiplicative convolution

01:14:14.410 --> 01:14:15.070 align:middle line:90%
structure.

01:14:15.070 --> 01:14:17.810 align:middle line:90%


01:14:17.810 --> 01:14:20.090 align:middle line:84%
I guess another thing that
I used without saying it

01:14:20.090 --> 01:14:23.490 align:middle line:84%
as clearly as I should have is
that we use that, pointwise, f

01:14:23.490 --> 01:14:26.570 align:middle line:90%
and g are bounded by around 1.

01:14:26.570 --> 01:14:28.890 align:middle line:84%
And that comes about for
the following reason.

01:14:28.890 --> 01:14:30.370 align:middle line:84%
Pointwise, all of
these functions

01:14:30.370 --> 01:14:34.650 align:middle line:84%
are bounded by 1
from the definitions.

01:14:34.650 --> 01:14:38.690 align:middle line:84%
And then, if you look
at f at a point N,

01:14:38.690 --> 01:14:41.950 align:middle line:84%
well, there are different
ways of factoring N.

01:14:41.950 --> 01:14:45.530 align:middle line:84%
And so they contribute
different amounts.

01:14:45.530 --> 01:14:48.190 align:middle line:84%
And there aren't very many
ways to factor a number,

01:14:48.190 --> 01:14:50.990 align:middle line:90%
and so f of N is pretty small.

01:14:50.990 --> 01:14:55.050 align:middle line:90%


01:14:55.050 --> 01:14:56.070 align:middle line:90%
And I think that's it.

01:14:56.070 --> 01:14:58.920 align:middle line:84%
I think that's all that we used
about R Ps and about primes.

01:14:58.920 --> 01:15:02.210 align:middle line:90%


01:15:02.210 --> 01:15:04.610 align:middle line:84%
Proving things about
primes is a funny business

01:15:04.610 --> 01:15:08.450 align:middle line:84%
because we don't know
that much about primes.

01:15:08.450 --> 01:15:13.350 align:middle line:84%
And so you have a theorem,
something about the primes,

01:15:13.350 --> 01:15:15.350 align:middle line:84%
you could ask, well, what
input about the primes

01:15:15.350 --> 01:15:16.990 align:middle line:90%
did we put into this theorem?

01:15:16.990 --> 01:15:20.390 align:middle line:84%
And there's not that
many different things

01:15:20.390 --> 01:15:23.650 align:middle line:84%
that we know how to
use as input anyway.

01:15:23.650 --> 01:15:25.530 align:middle line:84%
And so for today
it was this thing.

01:15:25.530 --> 01:15:33.430 align:middle line:90%


01:15:33.430 --> 01:15:34.070 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:15:34.070 --> 01:15:36.950 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: In the
Cauchy-Schwarz, what

01:15:36.950 --> 01:15:40.070 align:middle line:84%
about, do we always
lose something, or are

01:15:40.070 --> 01:15:44.650 align:middle line:84%
there other situations
like [INAUDIBLE]?

01:15:44.650 --> 01:15:45.950 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Good.

01:15:45.950 --> 01:15:47.090 align:middle line:90%
It's a great question.

01:15:47.090 --> 01:15:49.910 align:middle line:84%
And there is a specific
question, but the big picture

01:15:49.910 --> 01:15:52.430 align:middle line:84%
question was, at what
steps in this argument

01:15:52.430 --> 01:15:54.150 align:middle line:90%
did we lose something?

01:15:54.150 --> 01:15:57.750 align:middle line:90%
So we proved a theorem here.

01:15:57.750 --> 01:15:59.930 align:middle line:84%
It's a nice theorem, but
it's not the whole truth.

01:15:59.930 --> 01:16:02.347 align:middle line:84%
We put at the beginning the
conjectures of what we believe

01:16:02.347 --> 01:16:05.710 align:middle line:84%
are true, which are way stronger
than this in several respects.

01:16:05.710 --> 01:16:08.620 align:middle line:84%
Therefore, we must have lost
some things in this theorem.

01:16:08.620 --> 01:16:10.220 align:middle line:90%
Where did we lose them?

01:16:10.220 --> 01:16:12.900 align:middle line:90%
Let's think through the proof.

01:16:12.900 --> 01:16:15.040 align:middle line:90%
OK, so this is an equality.

01:16:15.040 --> 01:16:16.760 align:middle line:84%
The primes really
are this thing.

01:16:16.760 --> 01:16:18.440 align:middle line:84%
And this thing really
is a convolution,

01:16:18.440 --> 01:16:20.540 align:middle line:90%
so we haven't lost anything yet.

01:16:20.540 --> 01:16:24.060 align:middle line:84%
We can now break the convolution
up into pieces, like this.

01:16:24.060 --> 01:16:27.740 align:middle line:84%
I don't think we
lost too much here.

01:16:27.740 --> 01:16:30.480 align:middle line:84%
There is this very annoying
business about the I1,

01:16:30.480 --> 01:16:34.420 align:middle line:84%
I2 going over the edge, and
having to make I1 and I2 small.

01:16:34.420 --> 01:16:38.420 align:middle line:84%
So there is some loss associated
to that annoying business.

01:16:38.420 --> 01:16:41.320 align:middle line:90%
So that's one piece of loss.

01:16:41.320 --> 01:16:45.900 align:middle line:84%
Then let's just focus
on one of these pieces.

01:16:45.900 --> 01:16:48.500 align:middle line:84%
That piece got fed into
theorem A, so let's

01:16:48.500 --> 01:16:49.470 align:middle line:90%
switch the two boards.

01:16:49.470 --> 01:16:54.540 align:middle line:90%


01:16:54.540 --> 01:16:57.470 align:middle line:84%
So now we fed our piece
into this theorem.

01:16:57.470 --> 01:17:02.460 align:middle line:90%


01:17:02.460 --> 01:17:05.500 align:middle line:84%
This theorem is
not usually sharp.

01:17:05.500 --> 01:17:08.160 align:middle line:84%
So f and g are two
particular functions.

01:17:08.160 --> 01:17:12.360 align:middle line:84%
And for those two functions,
probably something much stronger

01:17:12.360 --> 01:17:15.040 align:middle line:90%
is true.

01:17:15.040 --> 01:17:20.420 align:middle line:84%
Let's think about where
we lost something.

01:17:20.420 --> 01:17:22.300 align:middle line:84%
So we wrote down
the left-hand side.

01:17:22.300 --> 01:17:24.280 align:middle line:90%
So far, so good.

01:17:24.280 --> 01:17:29.040 align:middle line:84%
Then, we applied the
proposition at, basically,

01:17:29.040 --> 01:17:30.620 align:middle line:90%
we said this is a convolution.

01:17:30.620 --> 01:17:32.960 align:middle line:84%
And you can bound the L-infinity
norm of the convolution

01:17:32.960 --> 01:17:36.400 align:middle line:84%
by the product of the L2
norms by Cauchy-Schwarz.

01:17:36.400 --> 01:17:41.000 align:middle line:90%
This step here is a big loser.

01:17:41.000 --> 01:17:46.280 align:middle line:84%
I didn't bring my red chalk, but
I would put a big red star here.

01:17:46.280 --> 01:17:47.750 align:middle line:90%
This is a big lossy step.

01:17:47.750 --> 01:17:53.520 align:middle line:90%


01:17:53.520 --> 01:17:58.400 align:middle line:84%
So remember that this guy is a
high part, so it has average 0,

01:17:58.400 --> 01:18:00.080 align:middle line:90%
and this guy has average 0.

01:18:00.080 --> 01:18:02.560 align:middle line:84%
When we convolve
them together there

01:18:02.560 --> 01:18:06.110 align:middle line:84%
are a lot of positive and
negative signs that appear.

01:18:06.110 --> 01:18:08.470 align:middle line:84%
Usually there will be
cancellation there,

01:18:08.470 --> 01:18:12.970 align:middle line:84%
but we didn't take advantage
of any of that cancellation.

01:18:12.970 --> 01:18:15.110 align:middle line:84%
We just used the
triangle inequality

01:18:15.110 --> 01:18:17.350 align:middle line:90%
and so we got this upper bound.

01:18:17.350 --> 01:18:21.110 align:middle line:90%
That's probably very lossy.

01:18:21.110 --> 01:18:23.030 align:middle line:84%
So for our particular
functions f and g,

01:18:23.030 --> 01:18:26.270 align:middle line:84%
that step was
probably very lossy.

01:18:26.270 --> 01:18:29.990 align:middle line:84%
Now this more general theorem
holds for any functions f and g,

01:18:29.990 --> 01:18:31.470 align:middle line:90%
which is nice.

01:18:31.470 --> 01:18:34.750 align:middle line:84%
If you could choose any f and
g, then for one particular q

01:18:34.750 --> 01:18:37.770 align:middle line:90%
that may well have been correct.

01:18:37.770 --> 01:18:40.830 align:middle line:84%
You could rig f and g so
that for one particular q

01:18:40.830 --> 01:18:44.270 align:middle line:90%
this Cauchy-Schwarz was sharp.

01:18:44.270 --> 01:18:46.350 align:middle line:84%
But I don't know
how to rig f and g

01:18:46.350 --> 01:18:52.230 align:middle line:84%
so that for most of these P's or
q's something like that happens.

01:18:52.230 --> 01:18:56.070 align:middle line:84%
It sounds even unlikely
to me that that is true.

01:18:56.070 --> 01:18:58.030 align:middle line:84%
So it's plausible
that without any more

01:18:58.030 --> 01:19:00.032 align:middle line:84%
input about prime
numbers, it's plausible

01:19:00.032 --> 01:19:02.240 align:middle line:84%
that there's a much stronger
version of this theorem.

01:19:02.240 --> 01:19:04.850 align:middle line:90%


01:19:04.850 --> 01:19:07.290 align:middle line:84%
But I have no idea
how to prove it.

01:19:07.290 --> 01:19:09.150 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that was
our big lossy step.

01:19:09.150 --> 01:19:10.630 align:middle line:84%
Then, we went on
to the next step.

01:19:10.630 --> 01:19:12.090 align:middle line:90%
We did this Cauchy-Schwarz.

01:19:12.090 --> 01:19:14.490 align:middle line:84%
I don't think this
one is so bad.

01:19:14.490 --> 01:19:16.190 align:middle line:84%
For this Cauchy-Schwarz
to be sharp,

01:19:16.190 --> 01:19:19.970 align:middle line:84%
we just means that
it would be sharp

01:19:19.970 --> 01:19:22.850 align:middle line:84%
if, for the different P's,
all these L2 norms were

01:19:22.850 --> 01:19:24.290 align:middle line:90%
about the same as each other.

01:19:24.290 --> 01:19:26.770 align:middle line:90%
I think that usually happens.

01:19:26.770 --> 01:19:29.930 align:middle line:84%
And then, we applied
the large sieve.

01:19:29.930 --> 01:19:35.890 align:middle line:84%
And the large sieve
itself is usually not

01:19:35.890 --> 01:19:39.610 align:middle line:90%
lossy in the key ranges.

01:19:39.610 --> 01:19:42.530 align:middle line:84%
So this is the really
important loss here

01:19:42.530 --> 01:19:46.850 align:middle line:84%
and would require a big,
new idea to do better.

01:19:46.850 --> 01:19:47.730 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:19:47.730 --> 01:19:49.650 align:middle line:90%
Nice questions, everybody.

01:19:49.650 --> 01:19:52.170 align:middle line:84%
Let's break there, but I'll
also hang out for office hours

01:19:52.170 --> 01:19:55.560 align:middle line:84%
if there are more things that
people want to talk about.

01:19:55.560 --> 01:20:03.000 align:middle line:90%